[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Reversed Accelerated Dragon with Early Nf3"]
[Black "Reversed Accelerated Dragon vs. Early Ng1-f3"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
{ The English has been a common visitor at top tournaments, both in classical, rapid and blitz time controls for decades. Most recently it was world champion Magnus Carlsen's main weapon against his challenger Fabiano Caruana in their recent world championship match. It is a flexible, positionally sound opening with potential for a complex and dangerous middle game. True, White does not directly occupy the centre in this opening, but opts for a more careful control of it. However, the hidden power of the White pieces should not be underestimated. If Black is not careful White will have the centre for good and dictate the game. Caruana had no trouble at all defusing Carlsen's opening play with the Black pieces. And, in this repertoire as well, we will see that Black is fine. We will fight for the centre right from the start and take the English bull by the horns, and hopefully have it for dinner ! }
1... e5
{ My proposed opening choice. We want to play a reversed form of the Sicilian Defense. This could be a hefty workload for those who are accustomed to playing 1. e4. But do not worry, the move is excellent. We open the road for our pieces, occupy the centre and immediately make clear our intentions to fight for every milimeter of the chess board. }
2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3
{ The move order which the World Champion used in the match.   3.g3  d5  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.Nf3   5.Bg2  is another way to play it, and this line will exclude Caruana's favourite line. We have another weapon prepared there though  (see Chapter 2)  .  5...Nc6  will reach the same position as in our main line. }
3... Nc6 4. g3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2
{ This is one of the most topical positions nowadays. White plays a form of Accelerated Dragon Reversed. Carlsen has been a Dragon afficionado for most of his life and his coach Peter-Heine Nielsen made a tremendously interesting DVD on the Sicilian Dragon itself. What did the contender prepare against this ? }
6... Bc5
{ The most aggressive reply to White's set-up. It looks risky, is relatively unexplored and has only started to gain track in the last couple of years. But, once one of the top guns tried it, everyone else started playing it. Caruana was one of its inventors. And he had a lot to say about the line in the match too. Over-the-board. So, this line is our first weapon of choice. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Reversed Accelerated Dragon with Early Nf3"]
[Black "Line 1.1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2
{ The Reversed Accelerated Dragon. } 6... Bc5
{ 'A new chapter in the opening theory'  (Yermolinsky)  It should be added that the main driving force behind this line is exactly Fabiano Caruana. This position arises with reversed colors after the moves: 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Bc4 Black is down a tempo and as you can see it it is the move Bc8-e6 that he is missing. But is this that bad ? The bishop does indeed protect the knight on d5, making tactical threats like Nf3xe5 less effective. Nevertheless, we should be aware of them. On the other hand, the bishop on e6 provokes some further activity by the white pieces. The knight jump on g5 being paticularly unpleasant. Still, an extra move is an extra move and Black has to be twice as careful when playing in the opening, especially with his d5-knight. Once he has managed to complete his development, he will have his dark-squared bishop actively placed on the a7-g1 diagonal and ready to support the fight for the d4-square.  For the above-mentiones reasons, the move   6...Nb6  remains the main line nowadays too. It is definitely playable but I want to present a fresh treatment of the opening.  The first moment in which White can give a try to the typical tactical shot: }
7. Nxe5 { It is harmless though. Black reacts with } 7... Nxc3
{ when White has three captures and only one of them leads to equality. } 8.
Nxc6 { loses the game after } 8... Qf6
{ with a double attack against the f2-pawn and the White queen. This is where the bishop performs at its best. }
*

