[Black "Line 1.1.1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2
{ The Reversed Accelerated Dragon. } 6... Bc5
{ 'A new chapter in the opening theory'  (Yermolinsky)  It should be added that the main driving force behind this line is exactly Fabiano Caruana. This position arises with reversed colors after the moves: 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Bc4 Black is down a tempo and as you can see it it is the move Bc8-e6 that he is missing. But is this that bad ? The bishop does indeed protect the knight on d5, making tactical threats like Nf3xe5 less effective. Nevertheless, we should be aware of them. On the other hand, the bishop on e6 provokes some further activity by the white pieces. The knight jump on g5 being paticularly unpleasant. Still, an extra move is an extra move and Black has to be twice as careful when playing in the opening, especially with his d5-knight. Once he has managed to complete his development, he will have his dark-squared bishop actively placed on the a7-g1 diagonal and ready to support the fight for the d4-square.  For the above-mentiones reasons, the move   6...Nb6  remains the main line nowadays too. It is definitely playable but I want to present you a fresh treatment of the opening.  The first moment in which White can give a try to the typical tactical shot }
7. Nxe5 { It is harmless though. Black reacts with } 7... Nxc3
{ when White has three captures and only one of them leads to equality. The second capture: }
8. Bxc6+ { is more interesting. Then after } 8... bxc6 { White can try either }
9. dxc3 Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 { but this allows } 10... Bxf2
{ when Black regains his pawn. The bishop cannot be trapped because of } 11. e3
f6 12. Nxc6 Bb7 13. Rf1 Bxg3 14. hxg3 Bxc6
{ And now Black is better thanks to his more active bishop. It controls the critical h1-square and next Black can simply advance his h- and g-pawns to create a strong passed pawn. }
