1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2
{ The Reversed Accelerated Dragon. } 6... Bc5
{ "A new chapter in the opening theory"  (Yermolinsky)  It should be added that the main driving force behind this line is exactly Fabiano Caruana. This position arises with reversed colors after the moves: 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Bc4 Black is down a tempo and as you can see it it is the move Bc8-e6 that he is missing. But is this that bad ? The bishop does indeed protect the knight on d5, making tactical threats like Nf3xe5 less effective. Nevertheless, we should be aware of them. On the other hand, the bishop on e6 provokes some further activity by the white pieces. The knight jump on g5 being paticularly unpleasant. Still, an extra move is an extra move and Black has to be twice as careful when playing in the opening, especially with his d5-knight. Once he has managed to complete his development, he will have his dark-squared bishop actively placed on the a7-g1 diagonal and ready to support the fight for the d4-square.  For the above-mentioned reasons, the move   6...Nb6  remains the main line nowadays too. It is definitely playable but I want to present you a fresh treatment of the opening. }
7. O-O O-O { The second moment in which White can try the central trick: } 8.
Nxe5 { and the second time it yields White nothing after } 8... Nxc3 9. bxc3
{ relatively best choice for White. } 9... Nxe5 10. d4 Bd6 11. dxe5 Bxe5 12.
Ba3
{ Or   12.Qc2  c6 =  Lorenz,M  (1970)  -Cetindag,E  (1862)  Schwarzach 2010 }
12... Re8 13. Qc2 Qf6 { 13...c6  14.Rad1  Qc7 =  is OK for Black too. } 14.
Rab1 { And here } 14... c6
{ was the simplest way to equality.  Rather than   14...Rb8  15.Qa4  with some problems on the queenside, Biegler,M  (2049)  -Ripperger,R  (2152)  St Ingbert 2000 }
