{ A major alternative is   8.Nxd5  which will be a subject of our next game. }
8... Re8
{ Caruana's star idea. He overprotects the e5-square and makes sure that the tricks on d5 will not work. At the same time he does not try to attack the bishop on c5 yet, as it may feel surprisingly more comfortable on the a3-f8 diagonal rather than on the a7-g1 one. The most aggressive line was tested by Fabiano a year ago at the Sochi Grand Prix tournament against Adams. Just as on move eight, }
9. Nxd5 { is still possible. Play may continue: } 9... Qxd5 10. Qc2 Qd6 11. a3
Bg4
{ If Black can develop this bishop more actively than with Bc8-e6, he should definitely do it. Now there is the positional threat of capturing on f3 and if White recaptures with the bishop- Nc6-d4xf3+ to spoil the opponent's pawn structure. }
12. b4 Bb6 13. Bb2 Rab8
{ This was enough for equality, but strictly speaking it was not necessary.  White would not have time to capture the pawn after the immediate:   13...Nd4 !?  14.Nxd4  exd4  15.Bxb7 ?!  Rxe2  Or after the preliminary   13...a5 !?  14.b5  Nd4  in both cases with very comfortable play for the second player. Once that the knights are traded, the e-file will be discovered for the black pieces and the backward pawn on e2 will bring a lot of worries for White. }
14. Nd2 { Yep, a blunder, but Black is OK in either case. } 14... Bxe2
{ 14.e3 =  and Black went on to capitalize on White's gross oversight, Chanut,E-Cwiek,P Condom 2002 }
