1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2
{ The Reversed Accelerated Dragon. } 6... Bc5
{ 'A new chapter in the opening theory'  (Yermolinsky)  It should be added that the main driving force behind this line is exactly Fabiano Caruana. This position arises with reversed colors after the moves: 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Bc4 Black is down a tempo and as you can see it is the move Bc8-e6 that he is missing. But is this that bad ? The bishop does indeed protect the knight on d5, thus making the tactical threats like Nf3xe5 less effective. Nevertheless, they exist. On the other hand, the bishop on e6 provokes some further activity by the white pieces. The knight jump on g5 being paticularly unpleasant. Still, an extra move is an extra move and Black has to be twice as careful when playing in the opening. Especially with his d5 knight. However, once that he manages to complete the development, he will have his dark-squared bishop actively placed on a7-g1 diagonal and ready to support the fight for the d4 square.  For the above-mentioned reasons, the move   6...Nb6  remains the main line nowadays too. It is definitely playable but I want to present you a fresh treatment of the opening. }
7. O-O O-O 8. d3
{ A major alternative is   8.Nxd5  which will be a subject of our next game. }
8... Re8
{ Caruana's star idea. He overprotects the e5 square and makes sure that the tricks on d5 would not work. At the same time he does not move the bishop from c5 yet, as it may feel surprisingly more comfortable on the a3-f8 diagonal rather than on the a7-g1 one. }
9. Bd2
{ Carlsen was definitely not taken by surprise as his opponent has tried this line as... both colors ! However, his opening choice does not yield him anything special and Caruana quickly equalizes. }
9... Nxc3 10. Bxc3 Nd4
{ The only other game was also a game by Caruana. His opponent Wesley So chose a different approach: }
11. Rc1 { which led him nowhere after } 11... Bb6 12. Re1 Bg4 13. Bxd4
{ 13.e3  giving up any hopes for an edge was the better choice-  Nxf3+  14.Bxf3  Bxf3  15.Qxf3  c6 = }
13... exd4 14. a3 c6 15. Nd2
{ A typical Dragon situation arose. The backwards pawn on e2 is a constant headache for White. If he somehow pushes it forward, Black will trade on e3 and there will be two hanging pawns on e3 and d3 that White will have to worry about. Black is already better, he is not risking anything at all and has a clear plan of ganging up on the e-pawn, and/ or advancing his kingside pawns to mate the enemy king. Now instead of the move in the game, something simple like: }
15... Qe7
{ followed by Ra8-d8-d6-e6  (or somewhere on the kingside)  would have consolidated Black's edge.  The game saw instead:   15...a5  16.Bf3  Be6  17.Qa4  Bc7  18.Ne4  Bd5  19.Nc5  Rb8  20.Bxd5  Qxd5  21.Qc4  and Wesley eventually equalized, So,W  (2778)  -Caruana,F  (2816)  Paris 2018 }
