[Black "Line 1.9.1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e5 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 Bc5 7. O-O O-O
{ 7...Be6 ?  leaves b7 undefended:  8.Nxe5  Nxe5  9.d4  Nxc3  10.bxc3  Bd6  11.dxe5  Bxe5  12.Bxb7  ±  (Marin) }
8. Nxd5 Qxd5 9. d3
{ Nakamura rejects the forcing line. This is more of a 'playing' attempt, rather than the struggle for an opening advantage.  Which starts after   9.Ng5  seee the next files for it. }
9... Qd8
{ The queen steps back, respecting the long range abilities of the White's fianchettoed bishop. In the process it takes under control the g5 square. Besides this move, Black has various ways of development. All of them seem fine for him. }
10. Be3 { Another typical Dragon idea. } 10... Bxe3
{ 10...Bb6 !?  is OK too, but Black has concrete idea on his mind. } 11. fxe3
e4
{ The reaction is also typical. Aronian ruins the pawn structure of his opponent, thus making it less mobile.  Although there is nothing wrong with   11...Be6  12.Rc1  f6 = }
12. dxe4 Qe7
{ Baburin calls the triple pawns 'Irish' pawns. Here they are isolated too and there is a constant danger they will disappear in the long run. }
13. Qc2 Bg4 { Intending Bg4-h5-g6 to aim at the most vulnerable pawn. } 14.
Rac1 Rad8
{ The remainer of the game is beyond our opening investigation. You can and should definitely study the game though, as well as many top games you can get your hands on in order to understand the lines properly. Check out the Model Games chapter for a more in-depth look. }
