1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e5 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 Bc5 7. O-O O-O
{ 7...Be6 ?  leaves b7 undefended:  8.Nxe5  Nxe5  9.d4  Nxc3  10.bxc3  Bd6  11.dxe5  Bxe5  12.Bxb7  ±  (Marin) }
8. Nxd5 Qxd5 9. d3
{ Nakamura rejects the forcing line. This is more of a 'playing' attempt, rather than the struggle for an opening advantage.  Which starts after   9.Ng5  The generally useful move: }
9... Bb6
{ is perfectly playable as well. The bishop steps back to a more stable position. }
10. b4
{ White tries to make use of the only drawback of the move Bc5-b6. The bishop no longer controls the b4 square.   10.Bd2  Bg4 =   10...Qd6 =  since there is no Nf3-d2-c4   e4  maneuver. }
10... e4
{ Paying back with the same coin.  Do better avoid   10...Nxb4 ?!  since after  11.Bb2  There is no adequate way of defending the e5 pawn.  f6  12.Nxe5  +=  For the more precise   10...a5 !  N  check the next example ! }
11. Ng5 Qd4 { The point behind Karjakin's play. } 12. Be3
{ The forcing play continues. } 12... Qxb4 13. Nxe4
{ This position was reached in two rapid games between both the opponents. }
13... Bxe3
{ The first one saw:   13...Bg4  14.h3  Bh5  15.Rb1  Qe7  16.Qd2  Rad8  17.Nc3  Here the simple   17.Rfc1  was giving White more pleasant game.  17...f6  18.Nd5  Qd7  19.Rfc1  He was also a tad better here too, but Black held, Nakamura,H  (2792)  -Karjakin,S  (2773)  Saint Louis 2017 }
14. fxe3 Qe7
{ This promises Black more chances for equality, although White can push further. }
15. Qd2 Ne5 16. Rac1 c6 17. Nc5 Ng4 18. e4 b6 19. Na4 Bb7
{ White won later, but at this stage of the game his position was not better. The center is hardly moving, Nakamura,H  (2792)  -Karjakin,S  (2773)  Saint Louis 2017. Still, I believe 10... a5 ! should be preferred. }
