[White "Reversed Accelerated Dragon with Early Nf3"]
[Black "Line 1.10.4 vs. The Principled 10.Nh7"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 Bc5 7. O-O O-O 8.
Nxd5 Qxd5 9. Ng5
{ The most direct try. White tries to make a tactical idea work. He chases Black's queen away from the centre and prepares for a double attack with Qd1-c2. }
9... Qd8
{ Marin called this move 'acceptable'. It is the more complex way to equalize, but at the same time allows you a chance to play for more. }
10. Nxh7
{ The only logical follow-up. It might be a shocker at a glance, but you do not need to freak out. }
10... Re8
{ Just remain calm and threaten to move the c5-bishop. Then the knight on h7 might end up surrounded by the black pieces.  Of course not:   10...Kxh7 ?  11.Qc2+  Kg8  12.Qxc5  ± }
11. Ng5 { Aronian simply clarifies matters. } 11... Qxg5 12. Bxc6
{ Before regaining the piece White makes sure there will be no active knight left on the board. In the process he destroys the opponent's pawn structure. }
12... bxc6 13. d4 Qh5 14. dxc5
{ White is up a pawn and has the better pawn structure. However, in positions with opposite-colored bishops the main factor is the activity of the bishops. As a rule, whoever has the more active bishop plays on this color complex and practically has an extra piece in the attack. Therefore, Black should be happy with the outcome of the opening. }
14... e4
{ Also   14...Bg4  =∞  should offer good compensation to Black  (Marin) } 15.
h4 Qg4 16. Bf4 Ba6 17. Re1 e3 { was also good, as } 18. Bxe3 { loses to } 18...
Rxe3 19. fxe3 Qxg3+ 20. Kh1 { 20.Kf1  Bc8 ! } 20... Re8 21. Qd4 Qh3+ 22. Kg1
Rxe3 { and White is helpless. } *

