{ The previous line was awesome and the fact that the challenger for the world championship title did not experience any problems equalizing against the world champion speaks for itself. However, what to do if White chooses this move order }
1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Bg2
{ Then our knight cannot stay in the centre, right ? My suggested repertoire starts with the retreat  Please note that we can use the same system against Carlsen's move order after   5.Nf3  Nc6  6.Bg2  Nde7  will transpose to our main lines in Chapter 2 and 3. If you feel like this is too much study material, then simply skip Chapter 1 and concentrate on the next ones. In any case, some extra material, functionality and flexibility cant hurt ; }
5... Ne7
{ Next we want to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop and play a reversed form of the positional Fianchetto system against the Sicilian. }
