{ The standard reaction. We need time to fianchetto the bishop on g7. So, it is crucial to keep any play in the centre by White under control. By playing a6 we make sure White can't play b5 and kick our knight away from c6, which would lessen our control of the d4-square.  Please make sure that you do not give up your e-pawn for that provocateur b-pawn   7...Nxb4 ?  8.Nxe5  ±  is all White wants from life.  White could also develop more calmly with }
8. Bb2 g6 { If White then goes } 9. h4
{ we should meet it with   9.a4  continues White's aggresive queenside expansion. }
9... h6 10. a4 { So that   10.h5  be answered  g5 } 10... Bg7 { Now } 11. b5
{ is best met with } 11... Nd4
{ NOTE  It makes no sense for you to open the a-file for White's pieces   11...axb5  12.axb5  Rxa1  13.Qxa1  Nd4 =  Although in this particular case it is not frightening for the second player, it will be better for you to remember it as an idea and wait for a good moment for the capture on b5. }
12. Nxd4
{ White often trades on d4 and sends the second knight in the centre  ideally we trade on b5 only when the queen cannot recapture back on a1, for example:   12.d3  axb5  13.axb5  Rxa1  14.Bxa1   14.Qxa1 ??  Nc2+  14...O-O =  On the other hand   12.e3  sends our knight back from the centre, but we are happy as the d3 point has been weakened-  Ne6  13.O-O  O-O = }
12... exd4 13. Ne4 O-O
{ However, as a rule this activity should not scare us- } 14. Nc5
{ is parried with } 14... Ra7 { With the great point worth remembering } 15.
bxa6 b6 { When the impudent } 16. Nb7
{ Self-traps the steed after  Best is   16.Nd3  Rxa6  =+  although Black is doing more than fine here with the a4-pawn as a clear target and White's bishop on b2 out of the game. }
16... Qd7 17. a5 Rxa6 18. axb6 Bxb7
{ 0-1  (18)  Mandekic,I  (2246)  - Rogic,D  (2482)  Zadar 2004  White resigned not waiting for   18...Bxb7  19.Bxb7  Rxb6 }
