[Black "Line 2.2.2 vs. Further Choice 8.Bb2"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Nc3 Ne7
{ A rare line. Black is heading for the Fianchetto system with colours reversed. It is a solid yet fighting way of playing it. The usual way of reaching this position as White is after the moves: 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Nde2 followed by 7. g2-g3 and 8. Bf1-g2. One advantage of this approach is that with colours reversed it is highly unexplored. In general though, Black should be careful when playing against a defense when White is up a tempo. This is why I believe that the positional systems should perform better than any of the sharper opening lines. My goal for Black with this repertoire is to equalize patiently and eventually play for more. Another advantage of the suggested line is that in most of cases Black can keep most of the pieces on the board. Which means that quick, dry draws are very unlikely. Skill and understanding of the resulting positions, and eventually mastery of them, will be the decisive factors. Please note that very often the games transpose to the usual Fianchetto system of the Dragon after say: 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Nde2 Nf6 7. g3 d6 }
6. Nf3 Nbc6 { The good news is that another supposedly dangerous line } 7. b4
{ This is considered dangerous against the usual Fianchetto line and here might be even more venomous. }
7... a6
{ The standard reaction. We need time to fianchetto the bishop on g7. So, it is crucial to keep any play in the centre by White under control. By playing a6 we make sure White can't play b5 and kick our knight away from c6, which would lessen our control of the d4-square.  Please make sure that you do not give up your e-pawn for that provocateur b-pawn   7...Nxb4 ?  8.Nxe5  ±  is all White wants from life.  White could also develop more calmly with }
8. Bb2 g6 { and continue his aggresive queenside expansion with } 9. a4
{ Our reaction is standard } 9... Bg7 10. b5 Nd4
{ Again avoiding the opening of the a-file. When White can still trade in the centre }
11. Nxd4 exd4 12. Ne4 O-O
{ If White now decides to delay the immediate attack against the b7-pawn and do something reasonable like }
13. O-O { We can use the given time to pile up pressure on the e2 pawn. } 13...
Re8
{ NOTE The e2-pawn is our best target after the knight swap on d4. We want to put as much pressure against it as we can, by doubling and sometimes even tripling major pieces against it. Playing Bg4 also helps a great deal. The ultimate goal is to force the e-pawn to move forward and this may lead to a weakening of White's entire pawn structure, and safety around his king. More holes in the pawn shield mean more access points. }
14. Qc2
{ Remember   14.Nc5  is nothing after  Ra7  Although here we have an additional resource   14...axb5  15.axb5  Rxa1  16.Qxa1  b6  17.Nb3  Nf5 =  with a discovered attack against the e2-pawn.  15.bxa6  b6  =+  Instead I suggest to keep our pawn structure intact with either }
14... Nd5
{ The game continuation saw   14...c6  but this does not seem too accurate. White got a slight advantage after  15.d3  cxb5  16.axb5  Nd5  17.Rfc1  Rb8  18.Qc5  +=  Mastrovasilis,A  (2543)  - Mchedlishvili,M  (2609)  Dresden 2007  Or with   14...Nf5 !?  when  15.Rfc1  is well met with  d3 !  16.exd3  Nd4 = }
15. d3 Qe7 16. bxa6 Rxa6 *

