1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Nc3 Ne7
{ A rare line. Black is heading for the Fianchetto system with colours reversed. It is a solid yet fighting way of playing it. The usual way of reaching this position as White is after the moves: 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Nde2 followed by 7. g2-g3 and 8. Bf1-g2. One advantage of this approach is that with colours reversed it is highly unexplored. In general though, Black should be careful when playing against a defense when White is up a tempo. This is why I believe that the positional systems should perform better than any of the sharper opening lines. My goal for Black with this repertoire is to equalize patiently and eventually play for more. Another advantage of the suggested line is that in most of cases Black can keep most of the pieces on the board. Which means that quick, dry draws are very unlikely. Skill and understanding of the resulting positions, and eventually mastery of them, will be the decisive factors. Please note that very often the games transpose to the usual Fianchetto system of the Dragon after say: 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Nde2 Nf6 7. g3 d6 }
6. Nf3 Nbc6 { The good news is that another supposedly dangerous line } 7. b4
{ This is considered dangerous against the usual Fianchetto line and here might be even more venomous. }
7... a6
{ The standard reaction. We need time to fianchetto the bishop on g7. So, it is crucial to keep any play in the centre by White under control. By playing a6 we make sure White can't play b5 and kick our knight away from c6, which would lessen our control of the d4-square.  Please make sure that you do not give up your e-pawn for that provocateur b-pawn   7...Nxb4 ?  8.Nxe5  ±  is all White wants from life.  There is also the normal development with }
8. Bb2 { and only after } 8... g6 9. a4
{ continues White's aggresive queenside expansion. Our reaction is standard }
9... Bg7 10. b5 Nd4
{ Again avoiding the opening of the a-file. When White can still trade in the centre or jump a knight into e4 at once. }
11. Ne4 { We already know that this is not dangerous at all. } 11... O-O 12.
O-O
{ Attentive readers most likely asked themselves if now taking on b5 is possible, since the e2-pawn is en prix. It is, but I would like to avoid the position after }
12... axb5 13. Nxd4
{ Instead   13.axb5  Rxa1  14.Bxa1 =  is equal.   14.Qxa1 ?  Nxe2+ } 13... exd4
14. axb5 Rxa1 15. Qxa1 Nf5 16. Rc1
{ I feel that the White pieces have too much freedom here. NOTE This is one thing that should guide us. Exchaning off pieces is as a rule not so bad for White since he is playing a reversed defense, meansing he has less space. Trades generally help the side that has less space. We would rather like to keep his pieces stepping on each other's toes. }
