{ The standard reaction. We need time to fianchetto the bishop on g7. So, it is crucial to keep any play in the centre by White under control. By playing a6 we make sure White can't play b5 and kick our knight away from c6, which would lessen our control of the d4-square.  Please make sure that you do not give up your e-pawn for that provocateur b-pawn   7...Nxb4 ?  8.Nxe5  ±  is all White wants from life.  The simple }
8. O-O { is always a candidate too. Then after } 8... g6
{ White has two major ideas } 9. Rb1
{ This is the most common. However, my gut feeling tells me that once that the rook leaves the a-file White also loses major part of the pressure he has there. After }
9... Bg7 10. d3
{ is no longer as venomous as before and Black can nicely arrange his pieces after }
10... O-O 11. a3 h6 12. e3 Bg4
{ Provocation ! It makes sense to lure White's pawn to h3 and win a tempo to be able to play Qd8-d7. }
13. h3 Be6 14. Qc2 Qd7 15. Kh2 Rad8
{ Black is active and ready for his kingside-central play, Suba,M  (2565)  - Franco Ocampos, Z  (2470)  Zaragoza 1996 }
