{ More dangerous seems the immediate } 9. a4 Bg7
{ Not   9...Nf5  as we did not castle yet and any opening of the game is too dangerous for us. Like  10.Ba3  f6  11.e3  Nxb4  12.g4  Nh6  13.g5  Nf7  14.d4  → }
10. Ba3 O-O
{ Leads to one of the most important positions of the whole line. The main question is whether White will benefit directly from having his extra tempi }
11. b5 Nd4
{ Let's wait again with the trade !  Especially when   11...axb5  12.axb5  Nd4  13.e3  Ne6  14.Qb3  ±  favours White. }
12. Ng5 { The major alternative is   12.e3  see the next file. } 12... axb5
{ Please note that Ba3 exerts pressure along the a3 - f8 diagonal, but every once in a while this bishop can become a target too. Like in this line   12...h6  13.Nge4  axb5  14.axb5  f5  15.Nc5  Rxa3 !?  16.Rxa3  Qd6  17.N3a4  b6  18.e3  bxc5  19.exd4  cxd4  =∞  Black's bishop pair and connected central pawns are ample compensation for the exchange. }
13. axb5 Rb8 14. Nge4 b6 15. Bxe7
{ This time the trade does not offer White any advantage.  Neither does   15.e3  Ne6  16.Bxe7  Qxe7  17.Nd5  Qd8  18.Nb4  Bb7  19.Ra7  Qd7 = }
15... Qxe7 16. e3 Ne6
{ Another little trick to note is   16...Be6  17.exd4  exd4  18.Ne2  f5  The central knight often gets surrounded if we are alert enough ! }
17. Nd5 Qd8 18. Nb4 Bd7 19. Nc3 e4 20. Bxe4 Bxc3 21. dxc3 Bxb5
