[White "Reversed Accelerated Dragon with 5. Bg2"]
[Black "Line 2.3.4- Beware! vs. Simple Development"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Nc3 Ne7
{ A rare line. Black is heading for the Fianchetto system with colours reversed. It is a solid yet fighting way of playing it. The usual way of reaching this position as White is after the moves: 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Nde2 followed by 7. g2-g3 and 8. Bf1-g2. One advantage of this approach is that with colours reversed it is highly unexplored. In general though, Black should be careful when playing against a defense when White is up a tempo. This is why I believe that the positional systems should perform better than any of the sharper opening lines. My goal for Black with this repertoire is to equalize patiently and eventually play for more. Another advantage of the suggested line is that in most of cases Black can keep most of the pieces on the board. Which means that quick, dry draws are very unlikely. Skill and understanding of the resulting positions, and eventually mastery of them, will be the decisive factors. Please note that very often the games transpose to the usual Fianchetto system of the Dragon after say: 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Nde2 Nf6 7. g3 d6 }
6. Nf3 Nbc6 7. b4
{ This is considered dangerous against the usual Fianchetto line and here might be even more venomous. }
7... a6
{ The standard reaction. We need time to fianchetto the bishop on g7. So, it is crucial to keep any play in the centre by White under control. By playing a6 we make sure White can't play b5 and kick our knight away from c6, which would lessen our control of the d4-square.  Please make sure that you do not give up your e-pawn for that provocateur b-pawn   7...Nxb4 ?  8.Nxe5  ±  is all White wants from life.  The simple }
8. O-O { is always a candidate too. Then after } 8... g6
{ More dangerous is the immediate } 9. a4 Bg7
{ Not   9...Nf5  as we did not castle yet and any opening of the game is too dangerous for us. Like  10.Ba3  f6  11.e3  Nxb4  12.g4  Nh6  13.g5  Nf7  14.d4  → }
10. Ba3 O-O
{ Leads to one of the most important positions of the whole line. The main question is whether White can benefit immediately from having these extra tempi. At a glance }
11. d3
{ does not seem as dangerous, but there is a lot of poison here ! We get time to finish the development }
11... Nd4 { White could still transfer his knight to the pivotal e4 square. }
12. Nd2
{ White can also go for   12.e3  Nxf3+   12...Ne6 !?  if you want to keep the game more complex, this is the way to play it.  13.Qxf3  But this gives us a choice between the solid   13.Bxf3  c6 =  13...c6  And the risky   13...Qxd3  14.Rac1  Qd7  15.Rfd1  Qe6  16.b5  f5  =∞ }
12... Rb8
{ After   12...Ne6  White has the dangerous sacrifice  13.e3 !  which we should not accept-  Qxd3  Better is   13...Rb8  14.b5  b6  15.Nc4  Re8  16.Rc1  +=  with queenside pressure.  14.b5  Qxc3  15.Bxe7  ±  Re8 ??  16.Ra3  Qb2  17.Nc4  +-  and the queen is trapped. }
13. e3 Ne6 14. b5 axb5 15. axb5 Re8 16. Qc2 b6
{ it seems as though Black has slowly made progress but here comes White's star idea. BEWARE of the following exchange }
17. Bxe7 Rxe7 18. Nd5
{ turns White's knights into monsters ! White is clearly better once he occupies the c6-outpost with the horsey, even if he doesn't win material on the spot right away. }
18... Rd7 19. Nb4 Bb7 20. Bxb7 Rxb7 21. Nc6
{ The rook is trapped, White is strategically winning, Castro Rojas,O  (2386)  - Echavarria,J  (2358)  Cartagena 2007 }
*

