1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Nc3 Ne7
{ A rare line. Black is heading for the Fianchetto system with colours reversed. It is a solid yet fighting way of playing it. The usual way of reaching this position as White is after the moves: 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Nde2 followed by 7. g2-g3 and 8. Bf1-g2. One advantage of this approach is that with colours reversed it is highly unexplored. In general though, Black should be careful when playing against a defense when White is up a tempo. This is why I believe that the positional systems should perform better than any of the sharper opening lines. My goal for Black with this repertoire is to equalize patiently and eventually play for more. Another advantage of the suggested line is that in most of cases Black can keep most of the pieces on the board. Which means that quick, dry draws are very unlikely. Skill and understanding of the resulting positions, and eventually mastery of them, will be the decisive factors. Please note that very often the games transpose to the usual Fianchetto system of the Dragon after say: 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Nde2 Nf6 7. g3 d6 }
6. Nf3 Nbc6 7. b4
{ This is considered dangerous against the usual Fianchetto line and here might be even more venomous. }
7... a6
{ The standard reaction. We need time to fianchetto the bishop on g7. So, it is crucial to keep any play in the centre by White under control. By playing a6 we make sure White can't play b5 and kick our knight away from c6, which would lessen our control of the d4-square.  Please make sure that you do not give up your e-pawn for that provocateur b-pawn   7...Nxb4 ?  8.Nxe5  ±  is all White wants from life. }
8. a3
{ Pruijssers decided to limit himself to some extra queenside space. There are other alternatives though }
8... g6 { There are other moves too, like } 9. d3
{ which will likely transpose later after Bc1-b2. But the following game has independent flavour }
9... Bg7 { Since the queenside bishop went to } 10. Bd2
{ Still, this development is not worrisome at all, we can continue with our ideas }
10... O-O 11. O-O h6
{ Black prevents the Nf3-g5-e4 manoeuvre for good and prepares the f7-f5 advance in the future. }
12. Rc1 Be6
{ We can still provoke some kingside weakness with   12...Bg4 !?  13.h3  Be6 }
13. Qc2
{ 13.Ne4  b6 =  BEWARE: an important moment of the game. Black needs to play the following moves b7-b6, Qd8-d7, Ra8-c8   d8  . But he needs to watch out for some little tricks in the process. Therefore }
13... Qd7
{ Was very inaccurate.  Better was either   13...b6  +=2  !  at once, with a good game after  14.Ne4  f5  Or the preliminary   13...Rc8  +=2  !  14.Ne4  b6  which is also excellent for the second player. }
14. Ne4 { Now this is awkward. } 14... Qd8
{ Black spotted the danger ! Admitting the mistake is very hard, but often, the only reasonable thing to do.   14...b6  drops a pawn after  15.Bxh6 !  Bxh6 ??  16.Nf6+  Please note that this is possible only because White's dark-squared bishop is on the c1-h6 diagonal. }
15. Nc5 Bc8 16. a4 b6 17. Nb3
{ Returning the favour.  Two extra tempi should have brought White the advantage. Better was   17.b5 !  axb5  18.axb5  bxc5  19.bxc6  += }
17... Be6 { But after another inaccuracy } 18. b5 { Black got the better game }
18... axb5 19. axb5 Na7
{ Hoffman,A  (2540)  -Lima,D  (2500)  Santa Clara 1994 } *

