[White "Reversed Accelerated Dragon with 5. Bg2"]
[Black "Line 2.4.2 vs. Slow Development 10.d3"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Nc3 Ne7
{ A rare line. Black is heading for the Fianchetto system with colours reversed. It is a solid yet fighting way of playing it. The usual way of reaching this position as White is after the moves: 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Nde2 followed by 7. g2-g3 and 8. Bf1-g2. One advantage of this approach is that with colours reversed it is highly unexplored. In general though, Black should be careful when playing against a defense when White is up a tempo. This is why I believe that the positional systems should perform better than any of the sharper opening lines. My goal for Black with this repertoire is to equalize patiently and eventually play for more. Another advantage of the suggested line is that in most of cases Black can keep most of the pieces on the board. Which means that quick, dry draws are very unlikely. Skill and understanding of the resulting positions, and eventually mastery of them, will be the decisive factors. Please note that very often the games transpose to the usual Fianchetto system of the Dragon after say: 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Nde2 Nf6 7. g3 d6 }
6. Nf3 Nbc6 7. b4
{ This is considered dangerous against the usual Fianchetto line and here might be even more venomous. }
7... a6
{ The standard reaction. We need time to fianchetto the bishop on g7. So, it is crucial to keep any play in the centre by White under control. By playing a6 we make sure White can't play b5 and kick our knight away from c6, which would lessen our control of the d4-square.  Please make sure that you do not give up your e-pawn for that provocateur b-pawn   7...Nxb4 ?  8.Nxe5  ±  is all White wants from life. }
8. a3
{ Pruijssers decided to limit himself with to extra queenside space. There are other alternatives though }
8... g6 9. Bb2 Bg7 { If } 10. d3
{ at once we can arrange our pieces in the following model way  Against other moves like   10.Qc2  O-O  11.O-O  We can react similarly  h6  following the same plan as above.  Or play like Rombaldoni-   11...Nf5  12.e3  Nd6  13.d4 ?!  exd4  14.Nxd4  Nxd4  15.exd4  Bf5  16.Ne4  Re8  ∓  Cordara,M  (2091)  -Rombaldoni,A  (2448)  Bratto 2010 }
10... O-O 11. O-O
{ yields no advantage to White after   11.Ng5  h6  12.Nge4  b6  13.O-O  Be6  1/2-1/2  (13)  Komljenovic,D  (2413)  - Garcia Fernandez, C  (2297)  Alcossebre 2015. Apparently, Komljenovic understood that he had done nothing creative so far and cleverly offered a draw to his lower-rated opponent. Black's play is easier-Qd8-d7, Ra8-d8, then f7-f5. }
11... h6
{ Prepares Bc8-e6, followed by Qd8-d7. This is our best set up, given that a White knight can never use the c5-square to troll us !  Although other reasonable moves like   11...Re8  should be good for equality too, say-  12.e3  h6  13.Qc2  f5  14.Rfe1  Be6  15.d4  e4  16.Nd2  Nd5 =  Fuchs,H  (2305)  -Noe,C  (2414)  Germany 2016 }
12. Rc1 Be6 13. Ne4 b6 14. Qc2 { Black should have played much simpler } 14...
Qd7
{ Now instead of the slightly artificial   14...Ra7  (which is a move we are normally not afraid to make in similar positions)  15.e3  Qd7  16.Rfd1  Rd8 ?  NOTE: d3-d4 break should be always carefully respected and ideally prevented even.   16...Bg4 !  was mandatory, and possibly still Ok for Black.  Now  17.d4 !  was devastating for Black  exd4  18.Nxd4  Nxd4  19.Bxd4  Bxd4  20.Rxd4  +-  White is completely winning once the centre opens up thanks to his superb pieces. Somehow Black survived this in Vassallo Barroche,M  (2384)  - Garcia Fernandez,C  (2372)  Valencia 2004 }
15. e3 Rad8
{ The only thing we need to worry about here is the central break d3-d4, which we easily stop with }
16. Rfd1 Bg4 17. Rd2 Qe6 *

