1. c4 Nf6 2. g3 e5 3. Bg2 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. O-O
{ The immediate   6.d4  exd4  7.Nxd4  is harmless for Black due to the strong check  Bb4+ }
6... Nde7
{ is another move order that we may employ. 6.... Nde7 comes just in time before White strikes in the centre with 7. d4 ! }
7. Nc3 g6
{ We have reached more or less the same position from the game Pruijssers-Tiviakov, with the inclusion of the moves O-O for White and g7-g6 for Black. White's best try for an opening advantage again remains }
8. b4 { Then after } 8... Bg7
{ We have defended the e5-pawn and no longer need the move a6 to prevent b5 from kicking our knight from c6.  Nevertheless, a lot of people still opt for   8...a6  which can easily transpose to our previous game with  9.a4  Bg7  10.Ba3  White can try now the immediate queenside expansion }
9. b5
{ Weak is   9.d3 ?  e4  Whereas   9.a3  O-O  would likely transpose to one of the lines we have covered in the variations game. }
9... Nd4
{ Now we have a further split With the pawn on b5 overextended, White needs to be careful }
10. Ne1 { Can be strongly met with } 10... a6
{ Normal is   10...O-O  11.e3  Ne6  12.a4  a6  13.Ba3  Re8  Here a strange-looking move like   13...Qd7 !?  14.d3  Rd8  puts pressure on the d3-pawn and does not allow White comfortable development. Black is good after  15.Qc2  axb5  16.axb5  Ra7 =  14.Qb3  Nf5  15.Nc2  axb5  16.axb5  Rb8  even this is close to equality, Purygin, A  (2257)  - Elistratov,I  (2180)  Samara 2012  Then if White tries to speculate with the pins }
11. Qa4
{ He may easily get into trouble after  Better is   11.bxa6  Rxa6  although Black enjoys excellent play against the isolated a-pawn in that case too. His plan is straightforward: double rooks on the a-file. }
11... O-O 12. e3 Nxb5 13. Nxb5 Bd7 *

