1. c4 Nf6 2. g3 e5 3. Bg2 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. O-O
{ The immediate   6.d4  exd4  7.Nxd4  is harmless for Black due to the strong check  Bb4+ }
6... Nde7
{ is another move order that we may employ. 6.... Nde7 comes just in time before White strikes in the centre with 7. d4 ! }
7. Nc3 g6
{ We have reached more or less the same position from the game Pruijssers-Tiviakov, with the inclusion of the moves O-O for White and g7-g6 for Black. White's best try for an opening advantage again remains }
8. b4 { Then after } 8... Bg7
{ We have defended the e5 pawn and no longer need the move a7-a6.  Nevertheless, a lot of people still opt for   8...a6  which can easily transpose to our previous game with  9.a4  Bg7  10.Ba3  Or the immediate queenside expansion }
9. b5
{ Weak is   9.d3 ?  e4  Whereas   9.a3  O-O  would likely transpose to one of the lines we have covered in the previous game. }
9... Nd4
{ now we're at another point where play branches off. Normal development with }
10. Bb2 { should be met with the same } 10... O-O
{ Remember, we do not open the a-file unless we are sure we can gain something out of this !   10...a6  11.a4  axb5  12.axb5  Rxa1  13.Qxa1  O-O  14.Nxd4  exd4  15.Ne4  Re8  16.Rc1  +=  is a bit better for White. NOTE A pair of rooks and minor pieces are traded which favours White since has less space and can now arrange his forces more freely. }
11. d3 a6
{ This is more logical than   11...c6  although Black can play this way too. For example  12.a4  If   12.bxc6  both  Nexc6 =  And   12...Nxf3+  13.Bxf3  Nxc6 =  leads to an approximately equal positions.  Now  12...a6  led to a slight advantage for White after  However, Black could and should have developed the bishop at once with   12...Bg4 !?  as he no longer needs to cover the b7-pawn. He is OK after, say  13.Nxd4  exd4  14.Ne4  Re8  X-raying the e2-pawn ! This also takes the sting out of  15.Nc5  Nd5  16.Nxb7  Qc7  17.bxc6  Bxe2  18.Qb3  Nc3  ⇆  with very active position for Black.  13.Ne4  axb5  14.Nxd4  exd4  15.axb5  Rxa1  16.Qxa1  cxb5  17.Ba3  +=  Corvi,M  (2319)  - Smole,A  (2116)  Lienz 2009 due to the weakness of the Black pawns.  Bd7  18.Nc5  Qc7  19.Nxd7  Qxd7  20.Qb2 }
12. a4 Be6
{ Not a bad move, although Black has two excellent alternatives instead  This is a good moment to trade stuff on the queenside   12...axb5 !?  13.axb5  Rxa1  Then if  14.Qxa1   14.Bxa1  gives White no tangible advantage after any reasonable move for Black  Bg4 =   14...Be6 =   14...b6 =  14...Bg4 !  =+  There will be a problem with the e2 pawn.  Also good is the immediate pressure against the e2 point   12...Bg4 !?  13.e3  Bxf3  14.Bxf3  Nxf3+  15.Qxf3  axb5  16.axb5  Rxa1  17.Rxa1  c6 = }
13. Nxd4
{ There is nothing for White neither after   13.e3  Nxf3+  14.Qxf3  axb5  15.axb5  Rxa1  16.Rxa1  b6 =  Nor after   13.Ne4  Bb3   13...Bd5 !? =  14.Qd2  Bd5  15.Nxd4  exd4 =  in both cases Black controls the centre and has no worries at all. }
13... exd4 14. Ne4 { Now a move worth remembering } 14... Bd5
{ The bishop is perfect on d5 and can always be replaced by a knight. Next we mount pressure along the e-file with good play }
15. Qc2 Re8 16. Rfc1 axb5 17. axb5 Rxa1 18. Rxa1 Nf5
{ Or   18...Nc8 !? =  followed by Nc8-b6 to cement the queenside.   18...Qd7 =  hitting b5 makes sense too. }
19. Ba3 h5
{ Schmidt, W-Sigurjonsson,G Nice 1974. Our chances are on the kingside and h5-h4 is on the agenda. }
