9. b5
{ Weak is   9.d3 ?  e4  Whereas   9.a3  O-O  would likely transpose to one of the lines we have covered in the previous game. }
9... Nd4
{ now we're at another point where play branches off. Very logical is the move }
10. a4 { After which we need to castle at once } 10... O-O
{ 10...Bg4  led to good position for Black after  11.Ba3  But I am afraid of   11.e3 !  N  Which frees the position in White's favour after  Nxf3+  12.Bxf3  Bxf3  13.Qxf3  Rb8  14.Ba3  O-O  15.Rfd1  Or the preliminary   15.e4  +=  15...Re8  16.d3  +=  11...Bxf3  12.exf3  O-O =  Danailov,S  (2425)  -Del Rio de Angelis, S  (2350)  Alcobendas 1994 }
11. Ba3 { Apparently, we need to limit ourselves to passive defense with }
11... a6
{ Instead the obvious   11...Re8  gave White a pull in an old game  12.Ng5  Rb8  13.Rc1  h6  14.Nge4  f5  Or   14...b6  15.e3  Ne6  16.Bxe7  Rxe7  17.Nd5  Rd7  18.Nb4  Bb7  19.Nc6  Bxc6  20.Rxc6  ±  with a very unpleasant opposite-coloured bishop middlegame for Black. The hole on c6 is a good stepping stone for White's pieces to launch an attack from.  15.Nc5  b6  16.Na6  Bxa6  17.bxa6  c5  18.a5  e4  19.d3  +=  White is better thanks to the long-term bishop pair prospects, Taimanov, M-Witkowski,S Dresden 1959 }
12. e3 Nxf3+ 13. Qxf3 Re8 14. Rfd1 axb5 15. axb5 Rb8
{ slowly building our position. White is more active at the moment, but since there are no weaknesses in our camp the advantage is only temporal. Next we will play Bc8-e6 and eventually prepare f7-f5 as usual. }
