[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Reversed Dragon"]
[Black "Line 2.6.1.1 vs. 9.a3"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
{ There are various ways with which we can come to the opening tabiya on move eight. In this game it all happened from the reversed King's Indian set up that White applied.  Our way of reaching the main position would be:   1.c4  e5  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.g3  d5  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.Bg2  Or   5.Nf3  Nc6  6.Bg2  Nde7  7.O-O  g6  8.d3  Bg7  5...Ne7  6.Nf3  Nbc6  7.d3  g6  8.O-O  Bg7 }
1... d5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 e5 4. d3 Nge7 5. O-O g6 6. c4 Bg7 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Nc3
Nde7
{ We have reached the proper Reversed Dragon Fianchetto system. White has a myriad of possibilities, but they lead to similar positions. Even though this is an opening repertoire course I advise you not to get too bogged down by remembering concrete lines, but to instead try to remember the typical ideas and common set ups that both sides are aiming for. The other way of achieving the same is: }
9. a3 { to which we simply castle } 9... O-O
{ White needs to prepare the pawn advance with either: } 10. Bd2
{ Apparently, White used way too many tempi in preparation for something which he could have done easier with a different move order. Black catches up in development and proves that his position is sound. We will see in the future that normal development does not necessarily lead to anything special for White. In fact he has a pleasant choice between }
10... h6
{ which prepares one of his main ideas with f7-f5 and deprives White of the manoeuvre Nf3-g5-e4.  And:   10...a5 !?  which is an idea that you can use of in case your opponent did not seize space on the queenside quick enough. Play may continue  11.Rb1  Nd4  12.b4  axb4  13.axb4  Bg4  14.Nxd4  exd4  15.Ne4  b6 =  in comparison to the lines with the early b2-b4 the open a-file is in Black's hands, Camerini, L-Ivanov,J  (2426)  Montecatini Terme 2003 }
11. b4 a6
{ Same policy as with 10... a7-a5 move. We want to slow the opponent's play on 'their flank' as much as possible in order to get enough time to play in the centre, and possibly on the kingside afterwards. }
12. Rc1 g5
{ Power play ! Black intends Ne7-g6 followed by f7-f5 and g5-g4, making use of the fact that the White knight on f3 does not have access to the d2 square.  There is nothing wrong with normal development though   12...Be6  13.Qc2  f5 =  g6-g5-g4 is still in the cards. It is all up to your taste if you want to act a bit faster or prepare it. }
13. Ne1
{ The knight will be quickly expelled from the centre after:   13.Ne4  f5  14.Nc5  Qd6  15.Be3  b6 = }
13... f5 14. Qb3+ Kh7 15. Nc2
{ While White manoeuvres in his camp his opponent seized the centre. } 15...
Ng6 { 15...Qd6 = } 16. Ne3 Nd4 17. Qd1 c6 18. Nc4 Be6
{ Black achieved everything that he wanted to in the game Elgabry,M  (2334)  - Salem,A  (2625)  Sharjah 2014. Even aesthetically Black's position is a joy for the human eye. }
