{ The threat is to capture on f3 followed by Nc6-d4xf3 if White does not want to ruin his pawn structure.  Although there is nothing wrong with the normal development as before-   10...h6  11.b4  Be6   11...a6 =  12.e3  Now b4-b5 is an unpleasant threat.  Black is not afraid of:   12.b5  Nd4  13.Nxd4  exd4  14.Ne4  b6 =  followed by a7-a6 with an eventual c7-c5 push on the agenda once the b5 pawn is removed. Please note that the knight on e4 does not have any active squares from where it can harm us and stands in the way of its own bishop. Also, if it ever moves, we are ready to meet it with Be6-d5 !  12...a6  13.Bb2  Qd7  14.Na4  b6 =  A typical position that can arise in this line. Black defended himself against the queenside assault and is ready to operate in the centre and on the kingside. The position is approximately level.  15.Rac1  Bh3  A bit more accurate was:   15...Rad8  16.Rfd1  Bg4  17.Rd2  Bh3 =  Since the central advance  18.d4 ?!  exd4  19.Nxd4  Bxg2  20.Kxg2  Bxd4  21.Bxd4  Qd5+  22.Kg1  Ne5  is favourable for Black only.  16.Rfd1  Bxg2  17.Kxg2  f5 ?  An instructive mistake. Black wants too much at once and does not pay enough attention to the central stability.   17...Rad8 =  would be still approximately even.  18.d4  Also good was:   18.Qb3+ !  Kh7  19.d4  e4  20.Ne5  ±  18...e4  19.Ne5  It was White who took care of the centre. After  Bxe5  20.Qb3+  Qd5  21.Qxd5+  Nxd5  22.dxe5  ±  White was clearly better, although the more experienced player as Black eventually won, Lima,F-Lima,D  (2475)  Brasilia 1997  Therefore }
11. e3
{ looks more or less forced, but then Black has pleasant play thanks to his active pieces and pressure along the d-file. }
11... Qd7 12. b4 Rad8 { The next natural move led White to disaster } 13. Rd1
{ He should have tried:   13.Ne1  a6  14.Ne4  b6  15.Bb2  Bh3 =  although Black is definitely happy here too.   13.b5  Na5  14.Ne1  c6  is good for Black. }
13... Qf5 { Ooops ! The pin is too painful for White. } 14. e4
{ This makes things even worse.   14.Nh4  Bxd1 } 14... Qh5 15. Ne1
{ 15.b5  Nd4  Or   15...Bxf3  16.Bxf3  Qxf3  17.bxc6  Nxc6  wins for Black anyway. }
15... Nd4 16. Qd2 Nb3 { Wining every single rook White has ! } 17. Qb2 Bxd1
{ 0-1  (17)  Stork,O  (1934)  - Van Foreest,J  (2519)  Luneburg, 2015 } *

