1. Nf3
{ There are various ways with which we can come to the opening tabiya on move eight. In this game it all happened from the reversed King's Indian set up that White applied.  Our way of reaching the main position would be:   1.c4  e5  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.g3  d5  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.Bg2  Or   5.Nf3  Nc6  6.Bg2  Nde7  7.O-O  g6  8.d3  Bg7  5...Ne7  6.Nf3  Nbc6  7.d3  g6  8.O-O  Bg7 }
1... d5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 e5 4. d3 Nge7 5. O-O g6 6. c4 Bg7 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Nc3
Nde7
{ We have reached the proper Reversed Dragon Fianchetto system. White has a myriad of possibilities, but they lead to similar positions. Even though this is an opening repertoire course I advise you not to get too bogged down by remembering concrete lines, but to instead try to remember the typical ideas and common set ups that both sides are aiming for. The other way of achieving the same is }
9. Be3
{ One of the common moves. The idea is similar to the one after 9. Bc1-d2 and 9. Bc1-g5. White prepares the trade of the dark-squared bishops after Qd1-d2   c1  followed by Be3-h6. One advantage over the other moves is that the bishop may decide to jump to c5. The drawback however is bigger it is vulnerable on e3 and stands in the way of the e7- knight. We proceed with the development as usual }
9... O-O 10. Rc1
{ Of course White does not necessarily need to go for a dark-squared bishop swap. He may choose to play on the queenside as usual as well.  We shouldn't worry about   10.Qd2  due to  Nf5  Hitting the bishop on e3, underlining the fact it is not great there.  There is nothing wrong with   10...Nd4 =  11.Bg5  f6  12.Be3  Nxe3  13.Qxe3  Nd4  =+  this was the course of the game Jovic,C  (2124)  - Lazic,M  (2461)  Vinkovci 2007. I already prefer Black as the bishop pair is a major asset in the long run. The closer we get to the endgame, the more powerful the bishops will become. We will see other games later where the dark-squared bishop in particular will go on a rampage in similar situations.   10.Qc1  would be similar to 11. Qd1-d2 after  Nf5  11.Bg5  f6  12.Bd2  Be6  13.b4  a6 =  followed by centralization of the Black pieces, Rind, B - Vukcevich,M  (2460)  USA, 1978 }
10... h6 { Again there is nothing wrong with:   10...Nd4 !? = } 11. a3
{ Or   11.Bc5  Re8  12.b4  Nd4  Easiest was to tame the White pawn with   12...a6  13.Nd2  Be6 =  13.Nd2  White is still doing nothing, but for some reason Black gave a pawn with:  Rb8  Instead   13...Ne6  14.Be3  Nf5 =  was good for the second player as in the above analyzed lines.  14.Bxa7  Ra8  15.Bc5  Ne6  ±  Benidze,D  (2495)  - Seyhanoglu, D  (2060)  Malatya, 2013 }
11... Nd4
{ Centralizing at once.  For those with a sound positional style I suggest:   11...Kh7 !?  12.Ne4  Then  Nd4  Black is ready to expel the White knight from e4, therefore the first player forces matters with  13.Bxd4  exd4  14.Qc2  and achieves nothing after the simple centralization  Nd5  15.Qc5  b6  16.Qc6  Rb8  Bc8-b7 is the threat.  17.Qa4  a6  18.Rfe1  c5  =+  Dalmagro,D - Needleman,A  (2419)  Dos Hermanas, 2003. Have a close look at this position. It is a triumph of Black's strategy. He got everything he needed: two bishops, space advantage, strong centre, clear play along the e-file and the kingside. Meanwhile White's play was lackluster and scattered. This what this line is all about ! }
12. Na4 { White wants to re-position his knight on c5. } 12... Nef5
{ 12...c6 =  Then wisely decides to keep his bishop pair- } 13. Bd2 Nxf3+ 14.
Bxf3 Nd4 { But Black is doing fine anyway. } 15. Bg2 Bg4
{ Provoking a concession. } 16. f3
{ On   16.Re1  Black can proceed with the simple  c6  Or try the cunning idea:   16...b6 !?  17.Bxa8  Qxa8  18.f3  Be6  19.Rc3  Rd8  =∞ }
16... Be6 { 16...Bf5 !? } 17. Nc5 Bd5 18. e3 Ne6 19. Qc2 Nxc5 20. Qxc5 c6
{ Gukhvat,P  (2243)  - Kobo,O  (2497)  Jerusalem 2016 } *

