{ We have reached the proper Reversed Dragon Fianchetto system. White has a myriad of possibilities, but they lead to similar positions. Even though this is an opening repertoire course I advise you not to get too bogged down by remembering concrete lines, but to instead try to remember the typical ideas and common set ups that both sides are aiming for. The third most common move. }
9. Bg5
{ Is not too frightening. Just like we often do with the manoeuvre Bc8-g4, White tries to provoke the move h7-h6 in order to put pressure on this pawn as early as possible. The thing is that we can castle at once and defend it with the king whenever needed. And that's not all, you can alread see that h7-h6 is as a rule useful move since it deprives White's knight of the dangerous manoeuvre Nf3-g5-e4. It is also something we do before advancing the f-pawn. Add to this the fact that White's bishop is not perfectly safe along the c1-h6 diagonal and you will understand why we should be rather happy when we see this move rather than afraid. }
9... h6 10. Be3 Nd4
{ An aggressive move ! Black's play is especially instructive in this game.  Easy equality is achieved after:   10...O-O  11.Qc1  Nf5  12.Bc5  Re8 = }
11. Nd2 Nef5 { Marinkovic goes for the dark-squared bishop. } 12. Nde4 Nxe3 13.
fxe3 Nf5
{ Black is already a bit better, since White's pawn centre already looks like a mess. Just notice how e3 weakened Black's kingside. }
14. Qd2 a5
{ Not a necessary move, but apparently Black does not want to hurry with the castling.   14...O-O  =+   14...c6  =+ }
15. a3 c6 16. Nc5
{ The knight is doing nothing there without the support of the other pieces. }
16... h5
{ Opens the cage for Black's bishop which does not have an opponent. The beast will soon hit the weak pawn on e3. }
17. Rfc1
{ Better seems the passive defence with   17.Nd1  although  (h4 ! ∓)  will further soften the dark squares. }
17... O-O 18. b4
{ The more White opens the game, the easier it gets for the bishops. This move in fact loses on the spot ! }
18... Bh6 19. Nd1 axb4 20. a4
{ A sad necessity.  Since   20.axb4  is met with  Rxa1  21.Rxa1  Nxe3 !  22.Nxe3  Qd4  -+ }
20... Ra7 { Intending b7-b6 followed by c6-c5 to keep the extra pawn. } 21. Ne4
{ Allows the last tactical blow.   21.Qxb4  Nxe3 } 21... Nxe3 22. Nxe3 Qd4
{ 0-1  (22)  Skirianoglou, D - Marinkovic,I  (2445)  Chania 1993  The resignation was not premature-   22...Qd4  23.Kf2  f5  24.Nc5  f4  25.gxf4  Qxf4+  Please not how all of Black's play was happening on the dark squares, the colour complex his opponent weakened when he gave up his bishop so early. }
