1... d5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 e5 4. d3 Nge7 5. O-O g6 6. c4 Bg7 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Nc3
Nde7
{ We have reached the proper Reversed Dragon Fianchetto system. White has a myriad of possibilities, but they lead to similar positions. Even though this is an opening repertoire course I advise you not to get too bogged down by remembering concrete lines, but to instead try to remember the typical ideas and common set ups that both sides are aiming for.The third most common move. }
9. Bg5
{ Is not too frightening. Just like we often do with the manoeuvre Bc8-g4, White tries to provoke the move h7-h6 in order to put pressure on this pawn as early as possible. The thing is that we can castle at once and defend it with the king whenever needed. And that's not all, you can alread see that h7-h6 is as a rule useful move since it deprives White's knight of the dangerous manoeuvre Nf3-g5-e4. It is also something we do before advancing the f-pawn. Add to this the fact that White's bishop is not perfectly safe along the c1-h6 diagonal and you will understand why we should be rather happy when we see this move rather than afraid. }
