1. Nf3
{ There are various ways with which we can come to the opening tabiya on move eight. In this game it all happened from the reversed King's Indian set up that White applied.  Our way of reaching the main position would be:   1.c4  e5  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.g3  d5  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.Bg2  Or   5.Nf3  Nc6  6.Bg2  Nde7  7.O-O  g6  8.d3  Bg7  5...Ne7  6.Nf3  Nbc6  7.d3  g6  8.O-O  Bg7 }
1... d5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 e5 4. d3 Nge7 5. O-O g6 6. c4 Bg7 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Nc3
Nde7
{ We have reached the proper Reversed Dragon Fianchetto system. White has a myriad of possibilities, but they lead to similar positions. Even though this is an opening repertoire course I advise you not to get too bogged down by remembering concrete lines, but to instead try to remember the typical ideas and common set ups that both sides are aiming for. There is not much aggression in the move }
9. a4 { The idea is to secure the c4-square for the White knight after } 9...
O-O 10. Nd2 Nd4 11. Nc4
{ However this is rather passive and I do not see what does White want to do further. Black simply finishes development }
11... c6 12. a5 Rb8 { 12...Bg4 !? =  at once is good as usual. } 13. Bg5 h6 14.
Be3 Bg4 15. h3 Be6 16. Ne4 Bd5
{ and experiences no problems at all. Black being the stronger player quickly outplayed his opponent after }
17. Bxd4 exd4 18. Qc2 f5 19. Ned2 Bxg2 20. Kxg2 g5 { 20...Nd5 !  =+ } 21. b4
Nd5
{ A very typical situation ! White's king is desperately weak, his pawn on e2 not only demands constant attention but also breaks the communication between the major pieces. The only thing you need to do is to arrange your pieces properly and break open the kingside. }
22. Rab1 Nc3 23. Rbe1 Qd5+ 24. Kh2 Rbd8 { Prevents any freeing e-pawn push. }
25. Nb1 Nxb1
{ 25...f4 !  at once would have deprived White of the next defensive resource.  26.Nxc3  dxc3  ∓ }
26. Rxb1 f4 27. Rbe1
{ 27.Nd2 !  followed by Nd2-e4 to cement the kingside was White's only chance. }
27... Rf7 28. gxf4
{ Invites the enemy pieces in.  It was not too late for   28.Nd2 !  Rdf8  29.g4 !  with chances for successful defence.  On the other hand   28.g4  f3 !  is awkward for White. }
28... Rxf4 29. Nd2 { Too late. } 29... Be5 30. Kg1 Qd7 31. Qc4+
{ 31.Kg2  allows sweet mate-  Rg4+ !  32.hxg4   32.Kh1  Rh4  32...Qxg4+  33.Kh1  Qh3+  34.Kg1  Qh2# }
31... Kh8 32. Ne4 Qxh3
{ 0-1  (32)  Vaca Kram,L  (2067)  - Leon Hoyos,M  (2428)  Mexico City 2006 } *

