1. Nf3
{ There are various ways with which we can come to the opening tabiya on move eight. In this game it all happened from the reversed King's Indian set up that White applied.  Our way of reaching the main position would be:   1.c4  e5  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.g3  d5  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.Bg2  Or   5.Nf3  Nc6  6.Bg2  Nde7  7.O-O  g6  8.d3  Bg7  5...Ne7  6.Nf3  Nbc6  7.d3  g6  8.O-O  Bg7 }
1... d5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 e5 4. d3 Nge7 5. O-O g6 6. c4 Bg7 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Nc3
Nde7
{ We have reached the proper Reversed Dragon Fianchetto system. White has a myriad of possibilities, but they lead to similar positions. Even though this is an opening repertoire course I advise you not to get too bogged down by remembering concrete lines, but to instead try to remember the typical ideas and common set ups that both sides are aiming for. The immediate central manoeuvre: }
9. Ne4 { is still on the cards. We proceed normally with the development: }
9... O-O
{ Although   9...h6  to prepare the usual f7-f5 is of course possible. One example runs:  10.Be3  O-O  11.Qd2  Nf5  12.Bc5  Re8  Just like in so many lines before the White pieces obstruct each other and are not harmoniously placed. Black can slowly push them back and gain space.  13.Rac1  a5 !?  If White does not go for b2-b4 himself we can always consider this move to expand on the queenside.   13...b6  14.Ba3  Bb7 =  14.b3  Bd7   14...Be6 !? =  Or   14...Nfd4 !? =  are both viable alternatives.  15.Rfd1  a4 !?  16.b4  b6  17.Be3  Nxe3  18.fxe3  a3  =+  Black won the bishop pair and limited the White knights, thus stands somewhat better, Marjanovic, Z - Ristic,N  (2382)  Dimitrovgrad 2003 }
10. Bg5 f6 11. Bd2 a5 12. Qa4 Kh8
{ Gives White something to play for.  Here   12...b6 =  followed by Bc8-b7 and then preparation for the f6-f5 advance with preliminary moves like h7-h6 and Kg8-h8   h7  seems like the simplest solution for Black. There is nothing that the White knight on e4 can do to us, it simply blocks their fianchettoed bishop. }
13. Rac1 f5 14. Nc3 Nd4 15. Bg5 c6
{ Although Black is pretty solid here as well, and went on to outplay his opponent after: }
16. Qa3 Re8 17. Nxd4 exd4 18. Na4 Ra6 { Provocation.   18...h6 !? = } 19. Nc5
Ra7 20. e4 { 20.Qb3  +=2  h6 = } 20... h6 21. Bxe7 Qxe7 22. Qb3 f4 23. Qb6
{ White should have gone for:   23.gxf4  Rf8  24.f5  gxf5  25.f4  ⇆ } 23... Ra8
24. Rfe1 Be5
{ The fianchettoed bishop is a sad picture, Black went on to win soon in Pivard, J - Manolov,I  (2350)  , Val Thorens 1989 }
