[White "Reversed Dragon"]
[Black "Line 2.6.9 vs. 9.Nd2"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
{ There are various ways with which we can come to the opening tabiya on move eight. In this game it all happened from the reversed King's Indian set up that White applied.  Our way of reaching the main position would be:   1.c4  e5  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.g3  d5  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.Bg2  Or   5.Nf3  Nc6  6.Bg2  Nde7  7.O-O  g6  8.d3  Bg7  5...Ne7  6.Nf3  Nbc6  7.d3  g6  8.O-O  Bg7 }
1... d5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 e5 4. d3 Nge7 5. O-O g6 6. c4 Bg7 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Nc3
Nde7
{ We have reached the proper Reversed Dragon Fianchetto system. White has a myriad of possibilities, but they lead to similar positions. Even though this is an opening repertoire course I advise you not to get too bogged down by remembering concrete lines, but to instead try to remember the typical ideas and common set ups that both sides are aiming for. }
9. Nd2
{ is similar to 9. a2-a4. White makes useful moves, but so does Black. After }
9... O-O 10. Nc4 Rb8 11. Be3 Nd4 12. Rc1 Bg4
{ Or the immediate   12...Be6  13.Ne4  Bd5 = } 13. h3 Be6
{ White's pieces look well placed, but ask yourself: what are they actually attacking ? How is White going to improve his position next ? On the other hand, Black has tons of improvement ideas. He can do h7-h6, followed by f7-f5-   f4  , or he may start pushing his queenside pawns with c7-c6, a7-a5 followed by b7-b5 and a5-a4 to grab more space there. Or finally, he can do some useful central moves with Rf8-e8 and/or Ne7-d5 in anticipation of the trade on d4 and the possible pressure along the e-file. The fact that Black has so many ideas and improvements means that he is STATICALLY BETTER and as long as the game remains slow, manoeuvring he will have the chance to improve his position, limitlessly. On the other hand White's pieces obstruct the motion of his own pawns. What follows is very typical }
14. b4 { 14.f4 ?  Nef5  15.Bf2  exf4  16.gxf4  Nh4  ∓ } 14... Nd5 15. Bxd4 exd4
16. Nxd5 Bxd5 17. Bxd5 Qxd5
{ White traded a bunch of pieces and is obviously worse. Just like in the above-mentioned game Vaca Kram,L  (2067)  - Leon Hoyos,M  (2428)  Mexico City 2006 the pawn on e2 is weak as well as the White kingside and Black is ready for both doubling of the rooks along the e-file or the direct kingside attack with f7-f5-f4 ! }
18. Qb3 { Was met well with } 18... Qh5
{ You need to make sure that the queens stay on the board as it is the White king which is under attack. }
19. Kg2 Rfe8 20. Rc2 Rxe2 21. Rxe2 Qxe2
{ and Black was a solid pawn up in Popescu, D  (2209)  - Nemeth,F  (2403)  Bucharest 2004 }
