[Black "Line 2.7.1 vs. Tricky Move Orders"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Bg2 Ne7 6. Nf3 Nbc6 7. d3
{ a move order which allows White an early bishop sortie. } 7... g6 8. Bg5
{ This is the point. Black also does this in the original Dragon. } 8... Bg7
{ Now he can try two ideas: } 9. Ne4 { To hit f6. Here I suggest: } 9... f5
{ to kick White's pieces back asap since they are not prepared for the assault.  On the other hand   9...O-O  can be met with the dangerous  10.Nf6+   10.Qc1  is not as dangerous-  Bf5  11.Nf6+  Kh8  12.Qc4  Qd6  since  13.Qh4  Qb4+  swaps queens.  10...Kh8  11.h4  h6  12.h5 !  Unnecessary with dangerous complications ! }
10. Nc5 { Of course not   10.Nf6+ ?  Kf7  which self-traps the knight.  Now }
10... Qd6
{ is playable and OK for Black. But I feel like there is a better continuation  (see next variation) }
11. Rc1 { Black will be OK after } 11... b6
{ Instead a game between two ladies saw:   11...Rb8 ?  This is too slow.  12.Qa4  O-O  13.Nd2  There was also a game where White went   13.Bxe7  Qxe7  14.Nd2  Qd6 ?  Now White could have won a pawn:  15.Nxb7  But he chose   15.O-O  e4  16.Rfd1  Nd4  and was already in bad shape, Shuraev,A  (2351)  - Krasovskiy,S  (2031)  St Petersburg 2013 CBM 156 Extra  15...Bxb7  16.Bxc6  Bxc6  17.Rxc6  ±  13...h6  The lesser evil was:   13...b6  14.Na6  Bxa6  15.Qxa6  Nd4  16.Bxe7  Qxe7  17.e3  Ne6  18.Bd5  +=  although White is better here too.  14.Bxe7  Qxe7  15.Qb3+  Winning a piece and the game.  Kh7  16.Bxc6  +-  bxc6  17.Qxb8  f4  18.Qb3  fxg3  19.hxg3  e4  20.Ncxe4  Bd4  21.Qc4  Bb6  22.Nf3  Kg7  23.Qc3+  Kh7  24.Neg5+  Kg8  25.Rxh6  Rf6  26.Ne4  1-0. }
12. Nb3 Be6 *

