1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Bg2 Ne7 6. Nf3 Nbc6 7. d3
{ a move order which allows White an early bishop sortie. } 7... g6 8. Bg5
{ This is the point. Black also does this in the original Dragon. } 8... Bg7
{ Now he can try two ideas } 9. Ne4 { to hit f6. Here I suggest: } 9... f5
{ to kick White's pieces back asap since they are not prepared for the assault.  On the other hand   9...O-O  can be met with the dangerous  10.Nf6+   10.Qc1  is not as dangerous-  Bf5  11.Nf6+  Kh8  12.Qc4  Qd6  since  13.Qh4  Qb4+  swaps queens.  10...Kh8  11.h4  h6  12.h5 !  was unnecessary and leads to dangerous complications ! }
10. Nc5
{ Of course not   10.Nf6+ ?  Kf7  which self-traps the knight.  But I feel that after saying "A" we need to proceed with "B", which is }
10... h6 { here. Moving the bishop away. Then } 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Rc1
{ Seems awkward, but we can castle: } 12... O-O
{ Not fearing the tactical blow: } 13. Nxb7
{ If White does not do anything at once, then   13.O-O  Qf7 =  Or   13...Kh7 =  are both OK for Black who will soon chase the annoying knight away.   13.Qb3+  Kh7  14.Nxb7  e4 !  ∓  is also bad for White.  Because of: }
13... e4
{ Not   13...Bxb7 ?  14.Qb3+  ±  Nor   13...Qb4+ ?!  14.Nd2  Bxb7  15.Bxc6  Bxc6  16.Rxc6  Qxb2  17.Rxg6  ± }
14. Nd2
{ Or   14.dxe4  fxe4  15.Nd2  Qf7  and Black wins a piece-  16.O-O  Bxb7  17.Bxe4  Nd8  ∓ }
14... Rb8 { Black takes over the initiative, for example } 15. Rxc6 Bxb7 16.
Rxg6 exd3
{ Or   16...e3 !?  If you feel materialistic, then   16...Kh7  wins the exchange and keeps some advantage for Black after  17.Rxg7+  Kxg7  =+ }
17. Bxb7 Rxb7 { with a strong attack against the White king. } *

