1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Bg2 Ne7 6. Nf3 Nbc6 7. d3
{ a move order which allows White an early bishop sortie. } 7... g6 8. Bg5
{ This is the point. Black also does this in the original Dragon. } 8... Bg7
{ Now he can try two ideas: either } 9. Qc1
{ to try and trade the fianchettoed bishop. I suggest that we do not make White happy and proceed with: }
9... h6 10. Bd2 Be6
{ As White cannot hold on to the h6-pawn forever. Sooner or later he will run out of useful moves, whereas we have ideas like Qd8-d7, Ra8-d8, f7-f5, b7-b6 and even g6-g5 to improve our position. Also note, that even though our castling is obstructed, we can still castle by hand, a la Botvinnik with Ke8-f8-g8-h7 ! The only game played in this line saw: }
11. Ne4 b6 12. h4
{ Or   12.O-O  Qd7 =  and if White stays, we can start moving the king towards h7. }
12... f5 13. Nc3 Qd7 14. Qd1
{ Admitting the failure of the whole plan. Now the simple } 14... O-O
{ was better for Black.  Although the game continuation   14...a6  15.Rc1  O-O  16.Qc2  Rac8  17.Qa4  Qd6  was good too, Dimitrov Iliev,I - Kolarov,A Sofia 1959 }
