1. c4 Nf6 { 1...e5  is our move order. } 2. Nc3
{ 2.a3  is another way to reach the position that we will discuss a bit later. }
2... e5 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. a3 g6 5. g3 Bg7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O d5
{ The simplest approach. We are getting into familiar waters.  Eljanov preferred to deviate from the central lines and chose instead:   7...d6  8.b4  Nd4  9.Bb2  c6  10.d3  Re8  Although Black was OK at this stage of the game this is a completely different cup of tea, Carlsen,M  (2802)  - Eljanov,P  (2742)  Moscow 2010 }
8. cxd5 Nxd5 { Except if White tries the tactical blow } 9. Nxe5
{ Then a forcing line goes } 9... Nxc3 10. Nxc6 Nxe2+ 11. Qxe2 bxc6 12. Bxc6
Rb8
{ White won a pawn but did not have the time to bring his queenside out. Therefore, he cannot count on any opening advantage. After }
13. d3 { Both } 13... Be6 14. Rb1 Ba2
{ It is again Black who can play for more after   14...Ba2  15.Ra1  Bd5  16.Bxd5  Qxd5  17.Rb1  Rb3  18.Rd1  Rd8 }
