[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Reversed Taimanov / Kan"]
[Black "Line 3.1 vs. 4.Nf3-Flexible"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. e3
{ White intends to play the Reversed Taimanov/ Scheveningen. This is quite a flexible set up and the Taimanov can easily transpose into the Scheveningen. The major difference in comparison to the Reversed Dragon is that the White light-squared bishop is not as actively posted on the long diagonal. White slowly builds their forces, looking for a good moment to strike in the centre with either d3-d4, or with e3-e4, or with e3-e4 followed by d3-d4. The play on the queenside remains a good idea for them too. However, as Uncle Yermo  (Alex Yermolinsky)  often says 'What works for Black does not necessarily work for White !' We shall see in the following lines that all these plans are not dangerous if we play correctly. }
3... Nc6
{ I suggest this move order, mainly to be prepared to deal with the immediate central push 4. d2-d4 !? The centre has a special meaning in the chess game, especially in the opening, therefore it always makes sense to keep a close eye on it. }
4. Nf3
{ Should be met with   4.d3  g6  would most likely transpose to the text and does not have independent meaning. }
4... Be7
{ We intend to castle and for the time being keep the d-pawn flexible. It may go to either d6 or d5, depending on the circumstances. We are still waiting for the move }
5. d4 { Which is the main move. } 5... exd4 6. Nxd4
{ 6.exd4  d5 =  was the original move order of the game Ding - Harikrishna, Riyadh 2017.  Here I suggest }
6... O-O
{ Unfortunately, we cannot free ourselves after   6...Nxd4  7.Qxd4  as d7-d5 is impossible. }
7. Be2 Bb4
{ Which either spoils the pawn structure of the opponent or/ and gives a chance to free ourselves with d7-d6. For example }
8. O-O
{ Please note that White cannot avoid the doubling of the pawns with   8.Bd2  as Black has all the comfort after  Nxd4  9.exd4  d5 =  Banas,J  (2275)  - Gasa,A  (2282)  Slovakia 2013 }
8... Bxc3 9. bxc3
{ The key position of the line. White has the bishop pair and a chance to build a strong centre after f2-f3 and e3-e4. Black on the other hand has a wonderful pawn structure and no weaknesses at all. In the long run he can hope to win one of the doubled c-pawns. Here are some practical examples }
9... Ne5
{ at once deserves attention as it gives us a chance to meet  Please watch out for White's key idea   9...d6  10.Nxc6  bxc6  11.Bf3  Bd7  12.c5 !  White effectively trades his weakness  (es)  and can hope for some advantage thanks to the bishop pair  d5  13.c4  Rb8  14.cxd5  cxd5  15.Qd4  +=  Rakhmanov, A  (2635)  - Anton Guijarro,D  (2646)  Havana 2018  Good seems also   9...Re8  10.f3   10.Nxc6  bxc6  11.Bf3  Ne4  ∞  10...d6  11.e4  But here White can decide to go for   11.Nxc6  bxc6  12.c5  this is not particularly dangerous however, due to  Nd5  13.Qd3  Qf6  ∞  11...Ne5  12.Qc2  c5 !?  Now  13.Nf5 ?!  led to advantage for Black after  Bxf5  14.exf5  d5  15.cxd5  c4  16.Rd1  Nxd5  ∓  Reinaldo Castineira,R  (2493)  - Starostits,I  (2449)  Santiago de Compostela 2018 }
10. f3 { with } 10... c5 11. Nb5 { and then } 11... d5
{ True, we are swapping off one of White's weaknesses, but we also send White's knight back to a poor position with }
12. cxd5 a6 13. Na3 Nxd5
{ and seize the centre, Smirin,I  (2594)  -Makhnev,D  (2449)  Batumi 2018 } *

