[White "Reversed Taimanov / Kan"]
[Black "Line 1.3.5-A vs. 4.Nf3-Flexible"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. e3
{ White intends to play the Reversed Taimanov/ Scheveningen. This is quite a flexible set up and the Taimanov can easily transpose into the Scheveningen. The major difference in comparison to the Reversed Dragon is that the White light-squared bishop is not as actively posted on the long diagonal. White slowly builds their forces, looking for a good moment to strike in the centre with either d3-d4, or with e3-e4, or with e3-e4 followed by d3-d4. The play on the queenside remains a good idea for them too. However, as Uncle Yermo  (Alex Yermolinsky)  often says 'What works for Black does not necessarily work for White !' We shall see in the following lines that all these plans are not dangerous if we play correctly. }
3... Nc6
{ I suggest this move order, mainly to be prepared to deal with the immediate central push 4. d2-d4 !? The centre has a special meaning in the chess game, especially in the opening, therefore it always makes sense to keep a close eye on it. }
4. Nf3
{ Should be met with   4.d3  g6  would most likely transpose to the text and does not have independent meaning. }
4... Be7
{ We intend to castle and for the time being keep the d-pawn flexible. It may go to either d6 or d5, depending on the circumstances. We are still waiting for the move }
5. a3
{ would most likely to transpose to later version of the game Morozevich - Karjakin. However, there are some independent continuations. }
5... d5 6. cxd5 Nxd5 { The less explored one being } 7. Bb5
{ Which leads to an aggressive version of the Four Knights variation in the reversed Sicilian. There are not so many games played in this line, but you better be prepared. Above all, there is no need to panic !  As usual, there is the developing move   7.Be2  which would transpose to Scheveningen positions as in the game Mareco - Macejia  The same comment from above applies to   7.d3  There is an interesting pawn sacrifice for lovers of the initiative with }
7... O-O
{ Or you can play it safe with   7...Nxc3  8.dxc3  Or   8.bxc3  O-O  when  9.Bxc6   9.d4  e4  10.Nd2  Bf5  ∞  is the better choice for White.  9...bxc6  10.Nxe5 ?!  is dubious due to  Qd5  11.Nf3  Ba6  ∓  White's king not only looks shaky, his h1-rook is cut off.  8...Qxd1+  9.Kxd1  f6  =+  with an excellent endgame for Black. }
8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. Nxe5 Nxc3 10. dxc3
{ Much worse is   10.bxc3 ?!  Qd5  11.Nf3  Ba6 !  ∓  and White is in danger of losing quickly. }
10... Bd6
{ Black has sufficient initiative even in the endgame after   10...Qxd1+  11.Kxd1  Bf6  12.Nf3  Or   12.Nxc6  Bb7  13.Nd4  Rad8  14.b4  Bxg2  =∞  12...Rd8+  13.Bd2  Bf5  =∞ }
11. Nc4 Ba6 12. Nxd6 cxd6 13. h4 Re8 14. f3 d5 15. Kf2
{ 1/2-1/2  (15)  Kozhuharov,S  (2424)  - Rusev, K  (2538)  Kozloduy 2018 The draw agreement came a bit early for Black. He could have kept on playing with c7-c5 in order to prepare d5-d4 and break open the position. His bishop is dominating, this is what matters most. }
