{ We intend to castle and for the time being keep the d-pawn flexible. It may go to either d6 or d5, depending on the circumstances. We are still waiting for the move }
5. a3
{ would most likely to transpose to a later version of the game Morozevich - Karjakin. However, there are some independent continuations. }
5... d5 6. cxd5 Nxd5 { Instead a Taimanov-like play with } 7. Qc2
{ is more common when  As usual, there is the developing move   7.Be2  which would transpose to Scheveningen positions as in the game Mareco - Macejia  The same comment from above applies to   7.d3 }
7... O-O { The main move is } 8. Nxd5 Qxd5 { When White can try either } 9. Bd3
{ To which there are many reasonable move, but I like Korneev's } 9... Kh8 10.
Bc4 { 10.Bxh7 ?  self-traps the bishop after  g6 } 10... Qd6 11. b4
{ when Black instructively took over the initiative after } 11... Bf6 12. Rb1
Ne7 13. d3 Bf5 14. Nd2 b5 15. Bxb5 Qd5 16. e4 Qxb5 17. exf5 Nxf5
{ and was a bit better already in Kovalyov,A  (2510)  - Korneev,O  (2587)  Alcala de Henares 2007 }
