1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. e3
{ White intends to play the Reversed Taimanov/ Scheveningen. This is quite a flexible set up and the Taimanov can easily transpose into the Scheveningen. The major difference in comparison to the Reversed Dragon is that the White light-squared bishop is not as actively posted on the long diagonal. White slowly builds their forces, looking for a good moment to strike in the centre with either d3-d4, or with e3-e4, or with e3-e4 followed by d3-d4. The play on the queenside remains a good idea for them too. However, as Uncle Yermo  (Alex Yermolinsky)  often says "What works for Black does not necessarily work for White !" We shall see in the following lines that all these plans are not dangerous if we play correctly. }
3... Nc6
{ I suggest this move order, mainly to be prepared to deal with the immediate central push 4. d2-d4 !? The centre has a special meaning in the chess game, especially in the opening, therefore it always makes sense to keep a close eye on it. }
4. a3
{ Definitely not the main move, but one of the many that might lead to the same. There are the following options   4.d3  g6  would most likely transpose to the text and does not have independent meaning. }
4... g6 5. d3
{ The move   5.Nf3  might transpose to the game after  Bg7  6.d3  The only independent try is   6.d4  exd4  check the text below after 5. d4 for that.  Or   6.Qc2  Or   6.Be2  these all lead to transposition.  There is also a quick queenside development, typical for many Sicilians with   5.b4  Bg7  6.Bb2  O-O  what are the dangers behind that move order demonstrates the model game Van Wely,L  (2655)  - Kasparov,G  (2820)  Tilburg 1997 CBM 061 }
5... Bg7 6. Nf3 O-O 7. Be2 d5 8. cxd5 Nxd5
{ So here we are, in another Fianchetto line, this time against the Scheveningen. It may arise after this move order 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. g3 e6 7. Bg2 Be7 8. O-O Nc6 as in the game Karpov,Anatoly  (2679)  - Fragkiadakis,Manolis, Rethymno sim Rethymno, 2001.  1  Luckily for White he is to move, otherwise Black would have played like Karpov 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. e5 Nd5 11. exd6 Qxd6 12. Ne4 claiming a slight, but long-term advantage thanks to his better queenside pawn structure. }
9. Qc2 { to which we can play like Karjakin } 9... a5
{ NOTE We are playing positional system and look for ways to prevent any play the opponent might get. They are stronger on the queenside but if we block them there the centre and the other wing will be ours and we can have pleasant, one-sided game. Or }
10. Bd2 Nb6
{ RULE OF THUMB: whenever you see Bc1-d2 in these situations that means that White wants to trade on d5 and put his bishop on c3. Therefore, just retreat and leave those two step on each other's toes !  There is also the capture on c3   10...Nxc3  11.Bxc3   11.bxc3  Qe7  Then  11...a4  Or   11...Be6  but my thinking is that the bishop on d2 and the knight on c3 are once again playing for the same squares, simultaneously blocking the c-file for White's major pieces. We want to keep it that way. }
11. Rc1 Kh8 { 11...a4 !? } 12. Nb5 f5 13. e4 Be6 14. b3
{ Now the nice regrouping } 14... Nc8 15. O-O Nd6
{ led to a very comfortable game for Black, Lobron,E  (2570)  - Oll,L  (2625)  New York, 1997 }
