1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. e3
{ White intends to play the Reversed Taimanov/ Scheveningen. This is quite a flexible set up and the Taimanov can easily transpose into the Scheveningen. The major difference in comparison to the Reversed Dragon is that the White light-squared bishop is not as actively posted on the long diagonal. White slowly builds their forces, looking for a good moment to strike in the centre with either d3-d4, or with e3-e4, or with e3-e4 followed by d3-d4. The play on the queenside remains a good idea for them too. However, as Uncle Yermo  (Alex Yermolinsky)  often says 'What works for Black does not necessarily work for White !' We shall see in the following lines that all these plans are not dangerous if we play correctly. }
3... Nc6
{ I suggest this move order, mainly to be prepared to deal with the immediate central push 4. d2-d4 !? The centre has a special meaning in the chess game, especially in the opening, therefore it always makes sense to keep a close eye on it. }
4. Nge2
{ In fact the Russian GM loved to play this way. The point is that   4.d3  g6  would most likely transpose to the text and does not have independent meaning. }
4... d5
{ is met with  However, since we know that the White knights are fighting for the same squares  (c3 and d5)  , there is an argument for   4...g6 !?  when  5.Ng3  Perhaps White should settle for   5.d4  exd4  6.Nxd4  Bg7 =  5...Bg7  6.Be2  d6  7.O-O  h5 !  Was already a bit awkward for White and Black soon got the upper hand-  8.f4  h4  9.Nge4  Nxe4  10.Nxe4  Bf5  =+  Tamaslacariu,I  (1831)  -Anton Guijarro,D  (2462)  Madrid 2011 }
5. Nxd5 Nxd5 6. cxd5 Qxd5 7. Nc3
{ Even this is nothing to worry about for us. Black's position is reliable with his free development and extra space. It might be OK for Black to trade a pair of knights in the Sicilian in order to give air to his pieces, but there the second player is playing for equalization ! In the English opening  (Reversed Sicilian)  we have this contradiction: White does not want to trade pieces in the fight for the edge, but at the same time needs to since he lacks space. }
7... Qd6
{ Or even   7...Qd8  When both  8.Bc4  And   8.Be2  Be6  9.O-O  Be7  10.a3  a5  11.d3  O-O  12.b3  Qd7 =  with pleasant position for Black, Ivanchuk,V  (2720)  - Kamsky,G  (2655)  Tilburg 1992  8...Be7  9.O-O  O-O  10.a3  Bf5  11.e4  Bg6  12.d3  Nd4 =  is less than nothing for White, Ten Hertog,H  (2353)  - Burg,T  (2504)  Wijchen 2014 }
8. Bc4 Be7 9. a3 O-O 10. b4 Bf5
{ Black's play is easy and obvious, his targets are easy to spot  (the d-file and the d3 square in particular)  . At the same time White needs some relief along the half-open file to castle. }
11. Bb2 Rad8 12. Nd5 Bg5 13. O-O Rd7
{ good enough for equality and a draw after  Here Black missed a chance to get some advantage with the tricky   13...b5 !  14.Bb3  Be4  15.Nc3  Bd3  16.Re1  a5  =+ }
14. d3 Qg6 15. e4 Be6
