[Result "*"]

1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e5 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. d3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4
{ The only major move that has independent flavour. White is heading for the Classical Sicilian Reversed.  Whereas   6.g3  g6  7.Bg2  Nde7  would transpose to the reversed Dragon  (see chapter 2) }
6... Nf6
{ You already know my logic about the positional systems against the reversed Sicilians and I hope you are not surprised by this choice. I believe that the knight is more useful here than on b6. It does not take the b6-square away from the dark-squared bishop after it has come to c5 from where it can exert a lot of pressure down the a7-g1 diagonal. And, in general the knight is better centralized on f6 from where it could jump into g4. Our play is easy and straightforward control and eventually occupy the d4-outpost with our pieces, put pressure on the backwards d3-pawn. From a strategical perspective we are aiming for positions where we have a good knight on d4 versus a poor bishop on e2, or opposite-coloured bishops with a mighty Black one on d4 !  Although Black has satisfactory results also after   6...Nb6  NOTE Alas, we cannot easily get into our beloved fianchetto with   6...Nde7  as this is one of those cases where the extra tempo really matters  7.Be3  g6  8.d4 !  is awkward for Black. }
7. Be2 { 7.Be3  allows  Ng4  where we see the utility of the knight. } 7... Bc5
{ Aiming a the vital d4-square. } 8. O-O O-O 9. h3 Re8
{ Protects e5 and prepares Black's next. } 10. Be3 Nd4 11. Rc1 c6
{ IMPORTANT: an instructive moment. I already mentioned a method that White often applies in order to close the weakness on d4 in the game Caruana - Karjakin. This method consists of a timely trade on d4 that forces Black to capture with the pawn. By doing so White achieves three things 1  Plugs the hole on d4 so that the Black pieces can no longer use it. 2  Blocks the half-open d-file which secures his backwards d3-pawn. 3  Creates a kingside pawn majority and can start attacking there. This is the reason why Tomashevsky moves away the pawn from c7, so that his queen no longer needs to protect it. }
12. Na4
{ Here   12.Bxd4  can be answered  Bxd4  13.Nxd4  Qxd4  =+  and the c7 pawn is no longer hanging. }
12... Nxf3+ 13. Bxf3 Bd4 14. Qd2 Qd6
{ Black has no problems whatsoever. Please check the model game Shinkevich - Tomashevsky. }
