6... Nf6
{ You already know my logic about the positional systems against the reversed Sicilians and I hope you are not surprised by this choice. I believe that the knight is more useful here than on b6. It does not take the b6-square away from the dark-squared bishop after it has come to c5 from where it can exert a lot of pressure down the a7-g1 diagonal. And, in general the knight is better centralized on f6 from where it could jump into g4. Our play is easy and straightforward control and eventually occupy the d4-outpost with our pieces, put pressure on the backwards d3-pawn. From a strategical perspective we are aiming for positions where we have a good knight on d4 versus a poor bishop on e2, or opposite-coloured bishops with a mighty Black one on d4 !  Although Black has satisfactory results also after   6...Nb6  NOTE Alas, we cannot easily get into our beloved fianchetto with   6...Nde7  as this is one of those cases where the extra tempo really matters  7.Be3  g6  8.d4 !  is awkward for Black. }
