{ The most direct approach for White in the Four Knights variation. The first player tries to seize the initiative at once, but this should not work as we are not even behind in development. 'One of Botvinnik's favourites in the past, this line is not too fashionable today.'  (Marin) }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4
{ The main move and a very obvious one. We are ready to spoil Whites pawn structure and/or free the centre with the timely d7-d5 move. White has three different approaches now. }
6. Bg5
{ is the old and quite aggressive move, but as we already stated-White should not be better prepared than us for the open play. A good reaction is }
6... h6
{ asking the bishop to choose on which diagonal it wants to stay first. } 7.
Bh4 { Followed by } 7... Bxc3+
{ The immediate   7...Ne5  allows and additional resource to White  8.Qb3  which leaves his pawns intact. }
8. bxc3 Ne5
{ The knight is not only hitting the weakness on c4, it is ready to jump to g6 and deprive White of his bishop pair. Now White has three main options }
9. e3 { is too modest to promise White anything } 9... Ng6 { After } 10. Bxf6
Qxf6 11. f4 d6 12. g3 a6
{ Black has an even better version of the main line and can play more aggressively with }
13. Bg2 c5 14. Ne2 O-O 15. Qd2 Rb8
{ Or the immediate   15...Qe7 !?  16.O-O  Bf5   16...Re8  17.e4  Bd7  ⇆  to put pressure on the e4 pawn is sufficient for equality as well.  Apparently Black does not need the complications after   15...Re8 !?  16.O-O  Bf5  17.Bxb7 }
16. a4
{ Better was   16.Rb1  Re8  although Black is doing great here as well. For example a move like  17.Rb6  will backfire after  Be6  18.Rxd6  Ne7 ! }
16... Re8 17. O-O Bf5 18. Rfd1 Qe6
{ with a clear advantage for the second player, Balberov,A  (2362)  - Obodchuk,A  (2368)  Nalchik 2016. This is the dream scenario for Black. White has no activity, just sits there passively defending of all his weaknesses. }
