[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. d4
{ The most direct approach for White in the Four Knights variation. The first player tries to seize the initiative at once, but this should not work as we are not even behind in development. 'One of Botvinnik's favourites in the past, this line is not too fashionable today.'  (Marin) }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4
{ The main move and a very obvious one. We are ready to spoil Whites pawn structure and/or free the centre with the timely d7-d5 move. White has three different approaches now. }
6. Bg5
{ is the old and quite aggressive move, but as we already stated-White should not be better prepared than us for the open play. A good reaction is }
6... h6
{ asking the bishop to choose on which diagonal it wants to stay first. } 7.
Bh4 { Followed by } 7... Bxc3+
{ The immediate   7...Ne5  allows and additional resource to White  8.Qb3  which leaves his pawns intact. }
8. bxc3 Ne5
{ The knight is not only hitting the weakness on c4, it is ready to jump to g6 and deprive White of his bishop pair. Now White has three main options }
9. f4 { attempts to seize the centre. Then } 9... Ng6 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. g3
{ Leads to a position where White indeed has extra space. However, his crippled pawn structure as well as the fact that two pairs of minor pieces have left the board means that A  He would not have sufficient kingside/central attack/ pressure. B  The weaknesses will be there til the end of the game and we can always try to get to them. Here are some model examples }
11... O-O
{ Black can and often starts with the manoeuvre   11...Nf8  12.Bg2  Ne6  This is also good and leads to equality, but we can do it on a later stage too  13.Qd2   13.O-O  O-O  14.e4  d6  15.Qd2   15.Rb1  Nc5  16.Qh5  c6  17.Rbd1  Be6 =  Zaiatz,E  (2395)  - Kosintseva,N  (2493)  Gorodets 2006   15.f5  Nc5  16.Nb5  Na6  17.Qd4  Re8 =  Khismatullin,D  (2534)  - Tomashevsky,E  (2480)  Moscow 2004  15...Bd7  16.Rae1  and a draw was agreed in Morozevich,A  (2741)  - Svidler,P  (2728)  Morelia/Linares 2007 CBM 117  13...O-O  14.Rb1  Nc5 =  Ivanchuk,V  (2704)  - Harikrishna,P  (2727)  Beijing 2014 }
12. Bg2 d6
{ I now recommend you the set up which is often used by the Serbian GM Nikola Nestorovic }
13. Qd2 Rd8 { Precisely here in order to dismiss the Nd4-b5 threat for good. }
14. O-O { 14.Nb5 ?!  c6 } 14... Nf8 15. Rab1 c6 16. e4 Ne6 17. Rbe1 Nc5 18. Re3
Na4 19. Rfe1 Be6
{ with a pleasant position for Black, Tisma,I  (2154)  - Nestorovic,N  (2449)  Kragujevac 2015 }
*

