{ has innocuous reputation for a reason. It only reinforces Blacks centre and the second player can easily get rid of the doubled pawns. Moreover, the lack of the knight on f3 is often a major problem for White as the opponent can easily build a strong kingside attack. After }
6... bxc6
{ White has tried various moves, with little to no success at all The other way of preventing the pawn doubling is }
7. Qc2 O-O 8. a3
{ is a bit too much. Even White cannot afford so many non-developing moves. We can play for the initiative with }
8... Bxc3+ 9. Qxc3 Ne4 10. Qc2
{ Or   10.Qd4  Re8  11.Be3  c5  12.Qd3  Qf6  13.Rb1  d6  and White can hardly move, Nagy,J  (2255)  - Groszpeter,A  (2493)  Hungary 2002 }
10... d5 11. e3 Bf5
{ Or even better   11...Qg5 !?  N  12.cxd5  cxd5  13.Qxc7  Bf5  =∞  with a strong attack to follow on the open files, as White did not castle yet. }
12. Bd3 Re8 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. O-O { Now the simple } 14... c5
{ would be awesome for Black. Please note that  Rather than   14...Qd7  15.Rd1  Bg6  16.b4  +=  Alcazar Jimenez,V  (2373)  - Pilgaard,K  (2432)  Madrid 2013 }
15. Bxe4 Bxe4 16. Qxc5 { is play with fire after } 16... Rc8 17. Qd4 Rc4 18.
Qd1
{ 18.Qxa7  Qg5  19.f3  Rc2  20.Rf2  Rxf2  21.Kxf2  Qh4+  22.Ke2  Bc2  is huge attack for Black. }
18... d4 *

