1. c4 e5 2. Nf3
{ The reversed Nimzovich variation in the Sicilian. Some people name it after Rubinstein. White immediately tries to attack the centre. Nowadays, it is widely explored by the Russian GM Rakhmanov, who also plays it as Black. Before him, a notable name to mention is Kortchnoi's second GM Y. Murey. The main drawback of the move is that we can push the pawn at once }
2... e4 3. Nd4 { Then develop comfortably with } 3... Nc6
{ Against the retreat } 4. Nc2 { We can simply expand } 4... d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 6.
Nc3 Qe5
{ It is not quite obvious why White needed to spend so much time in the opening for the manoeuvre Ng1-f3-d4-c2. After all the knight does not stand better there. No wonder Black has comfortable play. The most logical continuation is }
7. d4 exd3 8. Qxd3 Nf6 9. e4
{ Now we can trade the knight on c2 before it gets back into the game via e3 with }
9... Nb4
{ Although   9...Bc5  10.Be3  O-O  11.f4  Qh5  12.Be2  Bg4  13.Bxg4  Nxg4  14.Bxc5  Qxc5 =  is sufficient for the equality too, Macieja,B  (2592)  -Bu,X  (2637)  Stepanakert 2005 }
10. Nxb4 Bxb4 11. Qb5+ Qxb5 12. Bxb5+ Bd7 { Or   12...c6  13.Bd3  Be6 = } 13.
Bd3 O-O-O
{ with a pleasant endgame for Black, Rakhmanov,A  (2610)  - Shyam,S  (2481)  Dubai 2014 }
