1. c4 e5 2. Nf3
{ The reversed Nimzovich variation in the Sicilian. Some people name it after Rubinstein. White immediately tries to attack the centre. Nowadays, it is widely explored by the Russian GM Rakhmanov, who also plays it as Black. Before him, a notable name to mention is Kortchnoi's second GM Y. Murey. The main drawback of the move is that we can push the pawn at once }
2... e4 3. Nd4 { Then develop comfortably with } 3... Nc6
{ The most important idea of the line with reversed colours is to allow the doubling himself }
