1. c4 e5 2. Nf3
{ The reversed Nimzovich variation in the Sicilian. Some people name it after Rubinstein. White immediately tries to attack the centre. Nowadays, it is widely explored by the Russian GM Rakhmanov, who also plays it as Black. Before him, a notable name to mention is Kortchnoi's second GM Y. Murey. The main drawback of the move is that we can push the pawn at once }
2... e4 3. Nd4 { Then develop comfortably with } 3... Nc6
{ Yes, White can double our pawns with } 4. Nxc6 dxc6
{ But this will only open our bishops. My favourite set up is the most active one with Black bishops on f5 and c5. }
5. e3 { can be met with } 5... Nf6 6. h3 h5
{ I am generally trying to avoid this move as I find it often useless and sometimes even harmful for Black.  Therefore you can stick to the active development with   6...Bc5 !  see the lines below.  When }
7. Qb3
{ could have been effectively met with a typical manoeuvre worth remembering }
7... Nd7
{ 7...h4  8.Nc3  b6  9.Qc2  Bf5  10.b3  Qd7  11.Bb2  Be7  =+  Rakhmanov,A  (2641)  - Alsina Leal,D  (2521)  Linares 2016 }
8. d4 exd3 9. Qxd3 Qe7
{ Followed by g7-g6, bishop fianchetto and then Nd7-e5 or Nd7-c5 depending on the circumstances. }
*

