1. c4 e5 2. Nf3
{ The reversed Nimzovich variation in the Sicilian. Some people name it after Rubinstein. White immediately tries to attack the centre. Nowadays, it is widely explored by the Russian GM Rakhmanov, who also plays it as Black. Before him, a notable name to mention is Kortchnoi's second GM Y. Murey. The main drawback of the move is that we can push the pawn at once }
2... e4 3. Nd4 { Then develop comfortably with } 3... Nc6
{ Yes, White can double our pawns with } 4. Nxc6 dxc6
{ But this will only open our bishops. My favourite set up is the most active one with Black bishops on f5 and c5. The move }
5. b3
{ deprives White of the resource Qd1-b3 which may wreck havoc in Black's position, thus makes things easier for us. I suggest the active }
5... Bc5 6. e3 Bf5 7. Bb2
{ Black is not afraid of   7.g4 !?  Bg6  8.h4  h5  ⇆ } 7... Nf6 8. Nc3 Qd7
{ Or even better   8...Qe7  followed by the doubling of Blacks rooks along the d-file after O-O-O. }
9. h3 O-O-O { Christiansen, L  (2580)  - Comp Milano Pro USA 1996 } *

