[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nf3
{ The reversed Nimzovich variation in the Sicilian. Some people name it after Rubinstein. White immediately tries to attack the centre. Nowadays, it is widely explored by the Russian GM Rakhmanov, who also plays it as Black. Before him, a notable name to mention is Kortchnoi's second GM Y. Murey. The main drawback of the move is that we can push the pawn at once }
2... e4 3. Nd4 { Then develop comfortably with } 3... Nc6
{ Yes, White can double our pawns with } 4. Nxc6 dxc6
{ But this will only open our bishops. My favourite set up is the most active one with Black bishops on f5 and c5. }
5. Nc3 { The most flexible continuation. } 5... Nf6
{ You can also start with   5...Bf5  but I want to avoid  6.Qb3  True Black did well after  Bc5  7.e3  But White could have gone for the pawn   7.Qxb7  Ne7  and I find it unnecessary to analyse such possibilities when Black has an easy game by simply postponing the light-squared bishop's development.  7...Rb8  8.Qc2  Nf6  9.h3  h5  10.b3  Qd7  11.Bb2  Rd8 =  Murey,J  (2500)  - Lengyel,B  (2385)  Arnhem/ Amsterdam 1983  There is also the useful move }
6. h3
{ which deprives Blacks knight of the manoeuvre Nf6-g4 once White castles long. It also seems that White wants to expand on the kingside with g2-g4 and then attack our central pawn with Bf1-g2. But this plan is double-edged to say the least. With Whites king in the centre, it may easily backfire. Therefore just develop with }
6... Bc5
{ Keep the light-squared bishop at its original position to avoid Qd1-b3 for the time being. }
7. e3 Bf5 { And avoid   7...h5  you can always do it on a later stage.  Now }
8. g4 { is playing with fire, especially if White goes for the pawn } 8... Bg6
9. Bg2 { 9.Qb3  should be met with  Rb8 } 9... Qe7 10. Qc2 O-O-O 11. g5 Nd7
{ It transpires that the central pawn is poisoned } 12. Bxe4 Bb4
{ 12...Rde8  is also good. } 13. Bxg6 hxg6
{ There is no one to defend Whites kingside, say } 14. f4 Nc5 15. Kf1 Nd3 16.
Kg2 f6 { and the end is near for White. } *

