1. c4 e5 2. Nf3
{ The reversed Nimzovich variation in the Sicilian. Some people name it after Rubinstein. White immediately tries to attack the centre. Nowadays, it is widely explored by the Russian GM Rakhmanov, who also plays it as Black. Before him, a notable name to mention is Kortchnoi's second GM Y. Murey. The main drawback of the move is that we can push the pawn at once }
2... e4 3. Nd4 { Then develop comfortably with } 3... Nc6
{ Yes, White can double our pawns with } 4. Nxc6 dxc6
{ But this will only open our bishops. My favourite set up is the most active one with Black bishops on f5 and c5. }
5. Nc3 { The most flexible continuation. } 5... Nf6
{ You can also start with   5...Bf5  but I want to avoid  6.Qb3  True Black did well after  Bc5  7.e3  But White could have gone for the pawn   7.Qxb7  Ne7  and I find it unnecessary to analyze such possibilities when Black has easy game by simply postponing the light-squared bishop's development.  7...Rb8  8.Qc2  Nf6  9.h3  h5  10.b3  Qd7  11.Bb2  Rd8 =  Murey,J  (2500)  - Lengyel,B  (2385)  Arnhem/ Amsterdam 1983 }
6. e3
{ White's main plan is b2-b3, queenside fianchetto, Qd1-c2, O-O-O and then finally d2-d3. He often throws in a preliminary move like Qd1-b3 in order to force a queenside concession by Black. Black could have played more enterprising chess with either }
6... Bf5 { Then } 7. Qb3
{ is a bit unpleasant, since after   7.Qc2  Bc5   7...Qd7  8.b3  O-O-O  9.h3  h5   9...Qe6  10.Bb2  Nd7 =  Christiansen,L  (2555)  - Kaidanov,G  (2580)  Parsippany 1996  8.h3  Qe7 }
7... Rb8 { we can no longer castle long. } 8. Qc2
{ Nevertheless, Black is doing fine, at least from a positional point of view }
8... Qd7
{ 8...Bc5  transposes to Murey,J  (2500)  - Lengyel,B  (2385)  Arnhem/ Amsterdam 1983   see move  5...Bf5 }
9. b3 { Black was also good after } 9... Bd6 10. h3 h5 11. Bb2 Be5 12. O-O-O
Rd8 13. Na4 Bxb2+ 14. Nxb2 O-O 15. d4 c5 16. dxc5 Qe7 17. c6 bxc6
{ Rakhmanov,A  (2543)  - Vysochin,S  (2543)  Dagomys 2009 } *

