{ In this chapter we shall see some less explored but perfectly playable continuations that we may face. }
1. c4 e5 { From the original tries } 2. b3
{ has the benefit of controlling the long diagonal before us. However we have other ways of reaching good positions  We already discussed the move   2.a3 }
2... Nc6
{ At first I wanted to suggest the line   2...Nf6  3.Bb2  Nc6  4.e3  g6  5.d3  However, here is a spoiler of our plan   5.Nf3  Unfortunately we cannot do  e4 ?  here due to the pressure on the long diagonal  Still,   5...d6  is playable, but leads to different types of positions.  6.Ng5  Bg7  7.Nxe4  ±  5...Bg7  6.Nf3  d6  7.Be2  O-O  8.a3  Nd7   8...e4  9.dxe4  Nxe4  10.Bxg7  Kxg7 =  9.Nc3  a5  10.O-O  Re8  11.Nd2  Nc5  12.Nd5  Be6  Topalov,V  (2761)  - Aronian,L  (2792)  Paris 2016 }
3. Bb2 g6 4. g3 Bg7 5. Bg2 Nge7
{ Now d7-d5 is still in the air and if White tries to prevent it with } 6. Nc3
{ 6.Nf3  O-O = } 6... O-O 7. d3
{ Then Black can play on the kingside as the knight does not obstruct the f-pawn }
7... f5 8. Nd5 d6 9. a3
{ After   9.Qd2  there is the nice manoeuvre  Nd4  10.e3  Ne6 =  followed by c7-c6 and eventually d6-d5. }
9... Nxd5 10. Bxd5+ Kh8 11. Bg2
{ Now pay attention how nicely Black arranges his troops for the kingside attack }
11... Qe7 12. Qc2 Bd7 13. b4 Rae8
{ Just in time to have everyone where they are needed. } 14. b5 Nd8 15. Nf3 e4
{ and Black was already better in the game Djurovic,G  (2396)  - Bai,J  (2544)  Zadar 2016 }
