[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Van Wely, Loek vs. Kasparov, Garry"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 { This game demonstrates the dangers of the delayed castling by White. }
1... e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. e3 Nf6 4. a3 g6
{ An year before this game Van Wely faced:   4...d6  5.b4  g6  6.Bb2  Bg7  7.d3  O-O  8.Qc2  Re8  9.Nge2  Ne7  10.Ne4  Van Wely,L  (2605)  -Sokolov,I  (2670)  Amsterdam 1996 Which would have also been good for Black after:  d5 }
5. b4 Bg7 6. Bb2 O-O 7. d3 Re8
{ A strong novelty. In the Fianchettoe line against the Taimanov/ Kan Black often puts his rook on the e-file in order to threaten the powerful Nc6-d4 !  Kasparov deviates from a predecessor:   7...d5  8.cxd5  Nxd5  9.Nge2   9.Nxd5  Qxd5  10.Ne2  ∞  9...Nb6   9...Nde7 !? =  10.g3  Bf5  which was also great for Black in Rivas Pastor,M  (2515)  -Anand,V  (2710)  Madrid 1993 CBM }
8. Qc2
{ After:   8.Nf3  d5  9.cxd5  Nxd5  10.Nxd5  Qxd5  11.Be2  Kasparov's centralized queen would have given him a chance to play all over the board with:  a5 !  12.e4  Qb5  13.d4  Qb6  14.d5  Nd4  15.Qa4  Bg4  ∓  (Kasparov) }
8... d5 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Nxd5
{ Please note that White can no longer develop normally as the enemy pieces are too active:   10.Nge2 ??  Ndxb4 !  -+  is an instant win for Black. }
10... Qxd5 11. Ne2
{ Similar to the note above   11.Nf3  is met with  a5  12.e4  Qb5  13.d4  Qb6  14.d5  Nd4  ∓ }
11... f5 { frees the f7-square for the queen. } 12. Nc3 Qf7 13. Na4
{ 'The last straw.'  (Stohl)   13.Be2  was a must when Black is a little better after  Be6  14.O-O  Rad8  =+ }
13... Be6 14. Nc5 Bd5
{ Now the development of the kingside is stopped for good and White is in trouble. }
15. b5
{ And, if Black retreats White will get some air and time to develop with e3-e4 and Bf1-e2. Alas, this is never going to happen.  Probably Van Wely missed that   15.Nxb7 ?  loses to  Nd4 !!  16.exd4  exd4+  17.Be2   17.Kd1  Bb3  -+   17.Kd2  Bh6+  18.Kd1  Bb3  -+  17...Bxg2  18.O-O-O   18.Rg1  Bf3  18...Bxb7  -+  Whereas   15.e4  only makes things easier for the second player after  Nd4  16.Bxd4  exd4  17.Be2  Bc6  18.O-O  b6  ∓ }
15... Nd4
{ The star idea that we are always searching for when the opponent's king remains stuck in the centre. We can often sacrifice this knight for a mere pawn,so long as the White king remains in the center. }
16. exd4 exd4+ 17. Be2
{ After   17.Kd1  b6  -+  is the simplest, regaining the material with huge attack for free. }
17... Bxg2 18. O-O-O { Here Kasparov chose the materialistic } 18... Bxh1
{ Although, there was an argument for direct attack with:   18...c6 !  19.Rhg1   19.bxc6  Bxc6  20.Rhe1  b6  21.Nb3  Ba4  is game over.  19...Bd5  Not only does Black want to take a third pawn, but he is threatening to trap White's knight with b7-b6. White is busted, for example  20.bxc6  b6  with decisive material and positional advantage. }
19. Rxh1 Qd5 20. Re1 Re5
{ Nevertheless, Kasparov can be happy with his play. A rook and two pawns should be better than the two minor pieces of the opponent. And the closer the game leans towards an endgame, the bigger the difference becomes in favour of the rook. }
21. Qb3
{ Speaking of the endgame, Van Wely allows it. This makes Black's task easier.   21.f4 ?  wwould not work due to  Bh6  However   21.Nb3 !?  ∓  was White's best chance, although Black is clearly better here too. }
21... Qxb3 22. Nxb3 Rae8 23. Kd1
{ 23.Nxd4  drops more material to  R5e7  24.Kd2  Rd7  -+  (Kasparov) } 23...
Rxb5 24. Bf3 Rxe1+ 25. Kxe1
{ The endgame is won for Black. Kasparov demonstrated good technique after }
25... c6 26. Bd1 a5 27. Bxd4 a4 28. Bxg7 Kxg7 29. Nd2 Re5+ 30. Be2 b5
{ 30...Rc5  31.Nc4  b5  was more convincing. } 31. Kd1 Rd5 32. Kc2 g5 33. Bf3
Rd6 34. h3 Kg6 35. Nb1 h5 36. Nc3 g4 37. Bg2 Kf6 38. hxg4 hxg4 39. d4 Kg5 40.
Kd3 Rh6 41. Ke2 f4 42. Be4 Rh3 43. Kd2 Rh2 44. Ke1 g3 45. fxg3 fxg3 46. Kf1
Rf2+ 47. Kg1 b4 48. axb4 a3 49. d5 Kf4 50. Bg6
{ Or   50.dxc6  a2  51.Nxa2  Kxe4  52.Nc3+  Kf3  53.c7  Rc2  -+  (Kasparov) }
50... cxd5 51. Nxd5+ Kg5 *

