{ In this game we shall witness an unusual move order which reaches the main lines of the Reversed Dragon. }
1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. g3 Bg7 6. Bg2 e5 { Like that ! }
7. O-O Ne7 8. d3 Nbc6 9. Bd2 O-O 10. Rc1 Nd4
{ Not the only move, of course.  We are already familiar with the other excellent set-up:   10...h6  11.Ne4  b6  followed by Bc8-b7, Qd8-d7 and then f7-f5 with wonderful play for Black. }
11. Nxd4 exd4 12. Ne4 h6
{ The position is close to equality, but the next move by White makes his opponent fight for more. }
13. Qb3 { Quite an unfortunate square for the queen. } 13... b6
{ Excellent idea. } 14. Qc4
{ The poor white queen will suffer after   14.Nf6+ ?  Bxf6  15.Bxa8  Be6  -+  And the other tactical idea:   14.Bxh6 ?  does not work due to  Bxh6  15.Nf6+  Kg7  16.Bxa8  Bxc1  17.Rxc1  Kxf6  -+ }
14... c6
{ With the threat to trap the white knight after Bc8-e6 followed by f7-f5 ! }
15. Bb4 Bd7
{ This time   15...c5 ?  would be wrong due to  16.Nxc5 !  bxc5  17.Qxc5  ±  (Suetin)  Kortschnoj avoids the equality after:   15...Be6  16.Bxe7  Qxe7  17.Qxc6  Bxa2 =  which a clear sign of what he thinks about the position. }
16. Qa6
{ Another inaccuracy, but it is hard to give White good advise.  Perhaps he should have tried the prophylactical   16.Ba3 }
16... c5 { Now Black achieves everything he wants from his opening set-up. }
17. Ba3 Bc8 18. Qa4 a5 19. Qc2
{ There is still no:   19.Nf6+ ?  Bxf6  20.Bxa8  Bd7  -+ } 19... Nd5 20. Rce1
Re8
{ Black has a huge advantage. He is stronger in the centre and on both flanks, has more active pieces and more space. The bishop on a3 is blocked, and the other one will soon become toothless. The knight on e4 is a constant headache. This is how easily things can go horribly wrong for White, without even making any huge mistake. }
21. b3 { Next Kortschnoi brings his major pieces to the e-file. } 21... Ra7 22.
Bb2 Rae7 23. Qd1 { Plays on the kingside: } 23... f5 { 23...Bb7 !? } 24. Nd2 b5
{ And on the queenside too ! His position is that strong. The threat is Nd5-c3.  I suspect White did not like the possible blockade after   24...Nc3  25.Bxc3  dxc3  26.Nc4  b5  27.Ne3  ∓ }
25. Bxd5+ Qxd5 26. f3
{ A horrible move to make, but how else can White defend the long diagonal ? }
26... a4 { Huebner's position falls appart. } 27. Rf2
{ 27.bxa4  c4 !  -+  would be soon over. } 27... Ra7 28. Qc2 Be6 29. Rb1 g5 30.
Bc1 a3
{ Smothers the bishop and fixes the pawn on a2.   30...axb3  31.axb3  Rea8  -+  might have been easier though. }
31. Nf1 c4 32. bxc4 bxc4 33. Nd2 cxd3 34. exd3 Qxa2
{ Black won an important pawn and the game. } 35. Qxa2 Bxa2 36. Ra1 Rc8 37. Nf1
Bd5 38. Rxa3 Rxa3 39. Bxa3 Rc3 40. Bb2 Rxd3 41. Rd2 Rxd2 42. Nxd2 f4 43. gxf4
gxf4 44. Bc1 d3 45. Kg2 Kf7 46. Nb1
{ The best chance was   46.Ne4  Bxe4  47.fxe4  Be5  (Suetin) } 46... Ba2 47.
Nd2 Bd4 48. Nf1 Be5 49. Nd2 Bd5 50. Nb1 Ke6 51. Bd2 h5 52. Bb4 Bd4 53. Nd2 Be3
54. Bc3 Kf5 55. Nf1 h4 56. Nd2 Kg6 57. Ba5 Be6 58. Ne4 h3+ 59. Kf1 Bd5 60. Nd2
Kf5 61. Bc3 Ke6 62. Bb4 Kd7 63. Bc3 Kd6 64. Bb4+ Kc6 65. Bc3 Kb5 66. Ke1 Bg1
67. Nf1 Bxf3 68. Bd2 Be2 69. Bxf4 Bxf1 70. Kxf1 Bc5 71. Ke1 Kc4 72. Kd2 Bb4+
