1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ In this game we get the normal Nimtzowitch line, but the ideas are very much the same as the ones that we have after 1. c4 e5 2. Nf3 e4 3. Nd4 Nc6 4. Nc6 dc6. }
3. e5 Nd5 4. Nc3 Nxc3 5. dxc3 Nc6 6. Bc4 Qc7 7. Bf4
{ My favourite active set-up. } 7... e6 8. Qe2 h6
{ 8...d5  would not solve all Black problems after  9.exd6  Bxd6  10.Bg3  Bd7  11.O-O-O  Bf4+  12.Kb1  h6  13.Nd2 !  This should be already a familiar maneuver.  Bxg3  14.hxg3  Ne5  15.f4  Nxc4  16.Nxc4  O-O  17.Ne5  ±  Next White used the hook on h6 to build a decisive attack.  Rfd8  18.g4 !  Be8  19.g5  Rxd1+  20.Qxd1  Black needs to abandon the h6-pawn.  Qe7  Since   20...hxg5  21.Qh5  Kf8  22.Qh8+  Ke7  23.Qxg7  is hopeless for Black.  21.gxh6  g6  22.Qe1  +-  And White soon won:  Kh7  23.Ng4  f5  24.Ne5  Rd8  25.Nf3  e5  26.Qxe5  Qxe5  27.fxe5  Kh8  28.Kc1  Bc6  29.Ng5  Bxg2  30.Nf7+  1-0 Tseitlin,M-Zhuravliov,V/Soviet Union 1977/EXT 2002  (30) }
9. O-O { Castling kingside for a change } 9... b6 10. Rfd1 Bb7 11. Rd2 O-O-O
12. Rad1
{ All of this was very straightforward and easy to play, just like in our line. Now Grigor blunders with: }
12... f5
{ 12...g5  13.Bg3  g4  14.Nh4  Bg7  15.Rd6  this bind might have been Black's best chance.  And this unleashed the rooks: }
13. Rxd7 Rxd7 { 13...Qxd7  14.Rxd7  Kxd7  15.h4  ±  was more stubborn. } 14.
Bxe6 g5
{ Since   14...Nb8  15.Bxd7+  Nxd7  16.e6 !  wins on the spot after  Qxf4  17.exd7+  Kd8  18.Qe8+  Kc7  19.d8=Q# }
15. Rxd7 { With a decisive material advantage. } 15... Qxd7 16. Bxd7+ Kxd7 17.
e6+ Ke7 18. Ne5 Rg8 19. Nxc6+ Bxc6 20. Qe5 gxf4 21. Qc7+ Kxe6 22. Qxc6+ Bd6 23.
Kf1 Rg7 24. c4 Rd7 25. h4 Rd8 26. Ke2 Ke5 27. Kf3 h5 28. Qb7 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
