[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Carlsen, Magnus vs. Caruana, Fabiano - Game 4"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2
{ The Reversed Accelerated Dragon. } 6... Bc5
{ 'A new chapter in the opening theory'  (Yermolinsky)  It should be added that the main driving force behind this line is exactly Fabiano Caruana. This position arises with reversed colors after the moves: 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Bc4 Black is down a tempo and as you can see it it is the move Bc8-e6 that he is missing. But is this that bad ? The bishop does indeed protect the knight on d5, making tactical threats like Nf3xe5 less effective. Nevertheless, we should be aware of them. On the other hand, the bishop on e6 provokes some further activity by the white pieces. The knight jump on g5 being paticularly unpleasant. Still, an extra move is an extra move and Black has to be twice as careful when playing in the opening, especially with his d5-knight. Once he has managed to complete his development, he will have his dark-squared bishop actively placed on the a7-g1 diagonal and ready to support the fight for the d4-square.  For the above-mentioned reasons, the move   6...Nb6  remains the main line nowadays too. It is definitely playable but I want to present you a fresh treatment of the opening. }
7. O-O O-O 8. d3
{ A major alternative is   8.Nxd5  which will be a subject of our next game. }
8... Re8
{ Caruana's star idea. He overprotects the e5-square and makes sure that the tricks on d5 will not work. At the same time he does not try to attack the bishop on c5 yet, as it may feel surprisingly more comfortable on the a3-f8 diagonal rather than on the a7-g1 one. }
9. Bd2
{ Carlsen was definitely not taken by surprise as his opponent has tried this line as... both colors ! However, his opening choice does not yield him anything special and Caruana quickly equalizes. }
9... Nxc3 10. Bxc3
{ 10.bxc3  seems a bit illogical as it blocks the c-file for the rook, but it has been tested too. Black can proceed with the normal development:  Bg4  11.Re1  h6  12.Qc2  Qd7  13.Rad1  Bb6 =  And whenever chance occurs like here:  14.Be3 ?!  Grab it with the typical idea:  Bxe3  15.fxe3  e4 !  16.dxe4  Qe7  ∓  the tripled pawns might fall one after another, Galic,I  (2174)  -Majeric,Z  (2382)  Bizovac 2005 }
10... Nd4 11. b4
{ The World Champion uncorkes a novelty.  The only previous game played with this move was also a game of Caruana. His opponent Wesley So chose a different approach:   11.Rc1  which led him nowhere after  Bb6  12.Re1  Bg4  13.Bxd4   13.e3  giving up any hopes for an edge was the better choice-  Nxf3+  14.Bxf3  Bxf3  15.Qxf3  c6 =  13...exd4  14.a3  c6  15.Nd2  A typical Dragon situation arose. The backwards pawn on e2 is a constant headache for White. If he somehow pushes it forward, Black will trade on e3 and there will be two hanging pawns on e3 and d3 that White will have to worry about. Black is already better, he is not risking anything at all and has a clear plan of ganging up on the e-pawn, and/or advancing his kingside pawns to mate the enemy king. Now instead of the move in the game, something simple like:  Qe7  followed by Ra8-d8-d6-e6  (or somewhere on the kingside)  would have consolidated Black's edge.  The game instead saw the moves   15...a5  16.Bf3  Be6  17.Qa4  Bc7  18.Ne4  Bd5  19.Nc5  Rb8  20.Bxd5  Qxd5  21.Qc4  played, and So eventually equalized. So, W  (2778)  - Caruana,F  (2816)  Paris 2018 }
11... Bd6
{ This subtle move proves that the position is equal.The bishop steps away from the roaring queenside pawns. }
12. Rb1
{ If   12.Nxd4  exd4  13.Bxd4  The best way to regain the pawn is  Bxg3 !  Although Yermolinsky believes that Black is good after   13...Bxb4  14.Qa4  as well.  14.hxg3  Qxd4 = }
12... Nxf3+ 13. Bxf3 a6
{ Two pairs of knights disappeared and neither sides has significant chances for play on 'their' flanks. With the move in the game Caruana pre-emptively protects against White's possible 'minority attack' with the a and b-pawns. }
14. a4 c6 15. Re1
{ Or   15.b5  cxb5  There is nothing wrong with   15...axb5  16.axb5  Bd7  17.bxc6  Bxc6  18.Bxc6  bxc6 =  16.axb5  a5  which is OK for Black  (Yermolinsky)  . }
15... Bd7 16. e3 { 16.b5  axb5  17.axb5  cxb5  18.Bxb7  Ra4 = } 16... Qf6 17.
Be4 Bf5 { Some more pieces soon disappeared. } 18. Qf3 Bxe4 19. Qxf6 gxf6
{ The endgame is equal. } 20. dxe4 b5
{ Fixes the white pawn on a dark square. } 21. Red1 Bf8 22. axb5 axb5 23. Kg2
Red8 24. Rdc1 { Or   24.Rxd8  Rxd8  25.Rc1  Rc8  26.f4  c5 } 24... Kg7 25. Be1
Rdc8 26. Rc2 Ra4 27. Kf3 h5 28. Ke2 Kg6 29. h3 f5 30. exf5+ Kxf5 31. f3 Be7 32.
e4+ Ke6 33. Bd2 Bd6 34. Rbc1 *

