1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e5 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 Bc5 7. O-O O-O
{ 7...Be6 ?  leaves b7 undefended:  8.Nxe5  Nxe5  9.d4  Nxc3  10.bxc3  Bd6  11.dxe5  Bxe5  12.Bxb7  ±  (Marin) }
8. Nxd5 Qxd5 9. d3
{ Nakamura rejects the forcing line. This is more of a 'playing' attempt, rather than the struggle for an opening advantage.  Which starts after   9.Ng5 }
9... Qd8
{ The queen steps back, respecting the long range abilities of White's fianchettoed bishop, taking the g5-square under control in the process. Besides this move, Black has various other ways of developing, all of which seem fine. }
10. Be3
{ Another typical Dragon idea.  Against some normal development like:   10.Bd2  Black can regroup like this:  Qe7  11.Bc3  Bg4 =  followed by Ra8-d8, eventually Rf8-e8 and e5-e4 in the proper moment.  Against   10.Nd2  Black can proceed with the normal development  Bg4  Or   10...Be6  11.Ne4  Be7  12.Be3  Nd4 =  11.Ne4  Bb6 = }
10... Bxe3 { 10...Bb6 !?  is OK too, but Black has concrete idea on his mind. }
11. fxe3 e4
{ The reaction is also typical. Aronian ruins the pawn structure of his opponent, thus making it less mobile.  Although there is nothing wrong with   11...Be6  12.Rc1  f6 = }
12. dxe4 Qe7
{ Alex Baburin calls the triple pawns 'Irish' pawns. Here they are isolated as well and in constant danger of being picked off. }
13. Qc2 Bg4 { Intending Bg4-h5-g6 to aim the most vulnerable pawn. } 14. Rac1
Rad8
{ The remainer of the game is beyond our opening investigation. You can and should definitely study the game though, as well as many top games you can get your hands on in order to understand the lines properly. }
15. h3
{ 15.Nd4  Nxd4  16.exd4  Rxd4  17.Qxc7  Rd7  18.Qc2   18.Qc5  Bxe2 =  18...Rfd8 = }
15... Bc8 { 15...Be6 = } 16. a3 Rde8 { 16...Rfe8 = } 17. e5 h6 18. Qc5 Qxc5 19.
Rxc5 Ne7 20. Rxc7 Nd5 21. Rc5 Nxe3 22. Rfc1 Rd8 23. R1c3 Nxg2 24. Kxg2 Bf5 25.
