[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Carlsen, Magnus vs. Caruana, Fabiano - Game 9"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 Bc5 7. O-O O-O 8.
d3 Re8 { Caruana remains true to his move. } 9. Bg5
{ Not a novelty, but a new try by the world champion. } 9... Nxc3
{ The simplest solution.  Please note that the obvious:   9...f6 ?  fails tactically to  10.Qb3  Be6  11.Qxb7  when Black cannot profit from White's awkward queen position because many of his pieces are hanging.  Ndb4  12.Qb5  Be7  13.Bd2  Rb8  14.Qa4  and White is now simply up a pawn.  A case can be made for the preliminary   9...Nde7 !?  however, followed by either h7-h6 or f7-f6 in the future when White's provocation would not bring the desired result. }
10. bxc3 f6 11. Bc1
{ A previous game saw White going nowhere after:   11.Be3  Bxe3  12.fxe3  Be6  13.Qa4  Qe7   13...Ne7 !?  was good too.  14.Nh4  Qc5  and Black was already somewhat better in Curic,D  (2195)  -Majeric,Z  (2312)  Sibenik 2008 }
11... Be6 12. Bb2
{ Carlsen consistently prepares the advance of the d-pawn. But Black has many ways to meet it.   12.Nd2  to open the light-squared bishop  (Svidler)  can be answered  Qd7  13.Rb1  Bb6 = }
12... Bb6
{ Caruana moves the bishop pre-emptively away from c5 because the d-pawn will be coming to d4.  The computer's choice is not to the human liking but should be mentioned-   12...e4  13.dxe4  Qxd1  14.Rfxd1  Bc4  15.e3   15.Kf1  Rxe4  15...Rad8  with compensation. Although I believe White should be better. Even a move like:   15...Rxe4 ??  16.Nd2  16.Rd4 !?  could be an option, as long as the central pawns turn themselves into mobile avalanche.  Navara's suggestion of going   12...Qe7  with the idea to meet  13.d4  with  Rad8  seems very logical. For example:  14.e3  Bb6  15.Qc2  Qf7 =  In this line it is somewhat easier to organize a blockade on the light squares for Black. }
13. d4
{ A more ambitious try is   13.e4  but after  Bg4  White might not have time to advance the d-pawn at all. }
13... Bd5
{ But not   13...exd4  14.cxd4  Bc4  15.Re1  Ba5  16.Qc2 !  Ba6  17.Bc3  Bxc3  18.Qxc3  Rxe2  19.Rxe2  Bxe2  20.Qb3+  Kh8  21.Qxb7  ±  with a big advantage for White  (Yermolinsky) }
14. Qc2 exd4
{ A critical moment in the game. After a long think Caruana went for a concession.  Better was:   14...e4  to which Black probably feared:  15.Nh4  After   15.Nd2  e3  Black is doing fine, or maybe more than fine  (Svidler)  15...Na5 !   15...e3  might be risky after  16.fxe3  Rxe3  17.Nf5   17.Rf2 !?  +=  17...Bxg2  18.Nxe3  Bxf1  19.Rxf1  although Yermolinski likes Black I am honestly afraid of White's strong centre  16.Nf5  Nc4 ?!  However, Black has another way of meeting this idea. He can attack the centre with   16...c5 !  17.Ne3  Rc8 !  and reach an equal position after something like  18.Nxd5  Qxd5  19.dxc5  Bxc5  20.e3 =  (Svidelr)  The bishop pair is compensated by the black active pieces and his better pawn structure.  Now  17.Ne3 !  Nxe3  18.fxe3  leads to a position which would have been clearly better for Black if he had the chance to back up the central pawn with f6-f5. Then White's bishop on g2 would be excluded from the game forever. Alas, there is no time for this. Once he advances the c-pawn White will be better in this line  c6  19.c4  += }
15. cxd4 Be4 16. Qb3+ Bd5 17. Qd1 { Avoiding the repetition. } 17... Bxf3
{ Another concession after which White's position becomes definitely better.  Black should have stood his ground with   17...Qd7  18.e3  Rad8  putting the major pieces on the half-open files. The advance of White's centre afterwards would then be double edged as the pawns could easily become targets. For example:  19.Nd2  Ne7  20.Bxd5+  Or   20.e4  Bf7  21.Nb3  a5 !?   21...Qa4 !?  20...Nxd5  21.e4  Ne7  With two pairs of light pieces traded off Black does not risk getting checkmated and may hope to stop the centre in a profitable way. }
18. Qb3+ Kh8 19. Bxf3 Nxd4 20. Bxd4 Qxd4 21. e3 Qe5 22. Bxb7 Rad8 23. Rad1
{ is a bit better for the world champion. However, the fact that both players have opposite-colored bishops, and Caruana's solid position meant that he could Carlsen to a relatively easy draw. }
23... Qe7 24. h4 g6 25. h5 { A tad too early. } 25... gxh5 26. Qc4 f5 27. Bf3
h4 { Now the worst is over for the American grandmaster. } 28. Rxd8 Rxd8 29.
gxh4 Rg8+ 30. Kh1 Qf6 31. Qf4 Bc5 32. Rg1 Rxg1+ 33. Kxg1 Bd6 34. Qa4 f4 35.
Qxa7 fxe3 36. Qxe3 Qxh4 37. a4 Qf6 38. Bd1 Qe5 39. Qxe5+ Bxe5 40. a5 Kg7 41. a6
