1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Nc3 Ne7
{ A rare line. Black is heading for the Fianchetto system with colors reversed. It is a solid, but at the same time very fighting way of playing. The usual way of reaching this position  (with colors reversed)  is after the moves: 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Nde2 followed by 7. g2-g3 and 8. Bf1-g2. One advantage of this approach is that with colors reversed it is highly unexplored. In general, Black should be careful when playing against a defense when the opponent is up a tempo. This is why I believe that a positional approach to playing a system with colors reversed should perform better than playing sharper opening lines. My approach for this repertoire for Black is to patiently equalize and eventually play for more. Another advantage of my suggested approach is that most of the pieces will remain on the board, which means that we keep chances for a fight alive and it will come down to the player with the better understanding, skill, and mastery of the positions arising out of this opening which will decide the game. Please note that very often the games transpose to the usual Fianchetto system of the Dragon after say: 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Nde2 Nf6 7. g3 d6 }
6. Nf3 Nbc6 7. b4
{ This is considered dangerous against the usual Fianchetto line and here it might be even more venomous. }
7... a6
{ The standard reaction. We need time to fianchettoe the bishop on g7. So, White's activity in the centre should be nipped in the bud as much as possible.  Please make sure that you do not trade a central pawn for that provocator-   7...Nxb4 ?  8.Nxe5  ±  is all White wants from life. }
8. a3
{ Pruijssers decided to limit himself to some extra queenside space. There are other alternatives though: }
8... g6 9. Bb2 Bg7 10. O-O
{ Postponing the move d2-d3 for the time being.  Against other moves like:   10.Qc2  O-O  11.O-O  We can react similarly  h6  following the same plan as above.  Or play like Rombaldoni-   11...Nf5  12.e3  Nd6  13.d4 ?!  exd4  14.Nxd4  Nxd4  15.exd4  Bf5  16.Ne4  Re8  ∓  Cordara, M  (2091)  -Rombaldoni,A  (2448)  Bratto 2010 }
10... O-O 11. Rc1 Nd4
{ A typical thrust.   11...Bg4  is a tad too early without the h7-h6 move due to  12.h3  Be6  13.Ng5  +=  However, there is nothing wrong with our main set-up   11...h6 !?  12.Ne4  b6 = }
12. d3
{ Pruijssers finally goes for this.  Instead:   12.e3  is equal after  Nxf3+  13.Bxf3   13.Qxf3 !?  should be best met with:  c6 =  Since:   13...Qxd2  14.Ba1  Qd8  15.Rfd1  Qe8  =∞  once more looks risky for Black.  13...c6 = }
12... c6
{ I prefer the immediate development of the bishop with   12...Bg4 !?  13.Nxd4  exd4  14.Ne4  c6  15.Nc5  b6  16.Nb3  when Black is fine after any reasonable move:  Rc8 =   16...Be6 = }
13. Nd2 Bg4
{ Without the rook on a1, Black may also consider   13...a5 !?  to open up a line for his queenside rook  14.e3   14.bxa5  Qxa5  14...axb4  15.axb4  Ne6  Chances are more or less even here. }
14. h3 Be6 15. Nce4
{ Perhaps White should have tried:   15.e3 !?  Nb5  16.Nce4 } 15... Bd5
{ Black came out of the opening with a solid centre and good piece development. The first part of the game was a success. Next he needs to play mainly in the centre and on the kingside. But, this falls outside our opening repertoire. However, I do advise you to play through the rest of the game to get a better understanding of resulting middle game and endgame positions that can arise out of this opening. }
16. e3 Ne6 17. Nf3 Qc7 18. Qc2 Rad8
{ 18...Rfd8  19.Ned2  Bxf3  20.Nxf3  Rd7  21.Rfd1  Rad8  22.Rd2  Nf5 = } 19.
Ned2 Bxf3 20. Nxf3 Rd7 21. Rfd1 Rfd8 22. Rd2 Qd6 23. Rcd1 Nd5 24. Qb1 Nb6 25.
