1. c4 Nf6 2. g3 e5 3. Bg2 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. O-O
{ The immediate   6.d4  exd4  7.Nxd4  is harmless for Black due to the strong check  Bb4+ }
6... Nde7
{ is another move order that we may employ. 6... Nde7 comes just in time before White strikes in the centre with 7. d4 ! }
7. Nc3 g6
{ We have reached more or less the same position from the game Pruijssers-Tiviakov, with the inclusion of the moves O-O for White and g7-g6 for Black. White's best try for an opening advantage again remains: }
8. b4 { Then after: } 8... Bg7
{ We have defended the e5 pawn and no longer need the move a7-a6.  Nevertheless, a lot of people still opt for   8...a6  which can easily transpose to our previous game with:  9.a4  Bg7  10.Ba3  White has two major tries: }
9. Rb1
{ Weak is:   9.d3 ?  e4  Whereas   9.a3  O-O  would likely transpose to one of the lines we have covered in the previous game. }
9... O-O 10. d3 Nd4
{ Not a bad move.  However, I am sure you remember the plan from the previous game starting with:   10...h6  It is still good and valid, and you can stick to it. Further development of the game showed that Black has no worries at all after:  11.b5  Nd4  12.Ba3  Re8  13.Nxd4  This is just nothing for White.  Once more White's only hope for an edge is the not-so-obvious sacrifice of a pawn with:   13.e3  Nxf3+  14.Qxf3 !  when we can bite the bullet and go for the pawn grab  Qxd3  or patiently repel White's initiative with   14...Rb8  15.Rbc1  =∞  Qf5  16.Qd1  and play like Kortschnoi hoping to keep the pawn and turn it into a queen later.  13...exd4  14.Bxe7  Rxe7  15.Nd5  There is no real pressure on c7 which means that White's pieces can be driven back easily  Re5  16.Nb4  Better was:   16.e4  dxe3  17.Nxe3  =+  16...Rxb5  Black is not afraid of the complications that can arise after  17.Nc6  Rxb1  18.Nxd8  Rxd1  19.Rxd1  Rb8   19...c6 !?  ∓  20.Rb1  Bg4  21.Nc6  Re8  ∓  since he will be clearly better here. Pacovsky,J  (2285)  -Rumiancev,G  (2375)  Hradec Kralove 1995 }
11. Nd2
{ A logical regroupment. The knight will find a better place on both e4 and c4 squares.  Instead   11.Ne1  is timid and Black will have no worries at all after  c6  12.Bd2  Nd5  Or the standard   12...Bg4  13.h3  Be6  14.a4  Qd7  15.Kh2  Rad8 =  Another standard way of developing is   12...Be6 =  13.e3  Ne6  Black is OK after   13...Nxc3  14.Bxc3  Nb5  15.Bb2  Be6  16.a4  Nd6 =  14.b5  Nxc3  15.Bxc3  c5  16.Qc2  Rb8  17.Qa4  Qb6  18.Nc2  Bd7 =  Shumiakina,T  (2351)  -Shlakich,A  (2211)  St Petersburg 2008  If   11.Ng5  c6  12.Nge4  f5 !  13.Nc5  b6  is a tad better for Black. }
11... Rb8
{ Sufficient for equality would have been:   11...c6 !?  12.b5  Nd5 !  13.Nxd5  cxd5 }
12. b5 b6 13. Ba3 Bb7
{ It was not too late for:   13...a6 ! =  IMPORTANT: Black not only gets rid of a potential backward pawn on a7, he softens White's control on the vital c6 square. }
14. Bxb7 Rxb7 15. e3 Ne6 16. Nc4
{ Not bad, enough for an edge.  But even better was:   16.Nde4 !  Rb8  Or   16...Re8  17.Qf3  Rb8  18.Bxe7  Rxe7  19.Nd5 !  ±  when the central knights rule.  17.Bxe7  Qxe7  18.Nd5  Qd8  19.Nb4  ±  Ultimately landing on c6. We already know how painful this is from the previous game. }
16... Re8 17. Qf3 Rb8 18. Bxe7
{ The knights have gorgeous outposts and are more valuable than the bishops. }
18... Rxe7 19. Nd5 Rd7 20. Nb4 Ng5 21. Qg2 Qf6 22. f4
{ Apparently, this is one of those games where everything that can go wrong for one player does. I've included the rest of the moves as a warning of how not to do it. But also as inspiration to fight no matter what, in any given position !   22.Qc6 !?  ±  was very good for White too.  However, he should avoid:   22.Nc6 ?!  Nf3+  23.Kh1  Re8  24.Rfd1  a6  when Black is out of the woods. }
22... exf4 23. gxf4 Ne6 24. Ne5 Rd6 25. Nd5 { 25.Nbc6 !?  Re8  26.d4  ± } 25...
Qh4 26. d4 Re8 27. Nb4 f6 28. Nc4 Rd7 29. Nc6 Qh5 30. a4 Bf8
{ Up to this point in the game Moreno Ruiz was in complete control. However, the attempt to cash out with }
31. Nxa7
{ completely turned the tables in Black's favor !  Best was:   31.f5  Ng5  32.fxg6  Qxg6  33.Kh1  ±  with excellent winning chances.  Now comes a star move: }
31... Nxd4 { when the attack against the king turns out to be decisive ! } 32.
Kh1 { Alas, there is no   32.exd4  Rxd4  33.Rbc1  Bc5  34.Kh1  Re2  -+ } 32...
Nf5 33. Rbc1 Bb4
{ There was an alternative win:   33...Nxe3  34.Nxe3  Rxe3  35.Nc6  Re2  36.Qg3  Rd3 !  -+ }
34. Rb1 Nxe3 35. Nxe3 Rxe3 36. Nc6
{ Or   36.Rxb4  Re2  37.Qg3  Rdd2  and wins. } 36... Re2 37. Rf2 Rxf2 38. Qxf2
Rd2
{ White resigned not wishing to see   38...Rd2  39.Qg3  Qd5+  40.Kg1  Bc5+  A spectacular reversal of what seemed like a one side game for White. }
