1. Nf3
{ There are various move orders by which we can get to our tabiya position on move 8. In this game it all happened from the reversed King's Indian set up that White applied.  Our way of reaching the main position would be:   1.c4  e5  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.g3  d5  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.Bg2  Or   5.Nf3  Nc6  6.Bg2  Nde7  7.O-O  g6  8.d3  Bg7  5...Ne7  6.Nf3  Nbc6  7.d3  g6  8.O-O  Bg7 }
1... d5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 e5 4. d3 Nge7 5. O-O g6 6. c4 Bg7 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Nc3
Nde7
{ We have reached a proper Reversed Dragon Fianchetto system. White has a myriad of possibilities, but they lead to similar positions. I advise you not to study the concrete moves, but to pay attention to the typical ideas and the common set ups that both sides are aiming for. }
9. Rb1
{ My database indicates that this is the second most popular move played currently. White still finds nothing better but to start running the b-pawn. }
9... a5
{ Once again we are at a crossroads. To spoil or not to spoil, that is the question ! And the answer is... it's up to you ! Up to your taste, feeling, the way that you slept the previous night and the breakfast you had that day :  Here is how the game may proceed after the natural move:   9...O-O  10.b4  a6  Black wants to open the a-file for his rook and this should be good !  Although again there is a good alternative   10...Nd4 !? =  11.a3  Or   11.a4  Nd4  12.Nd2  c6  13.e3  Ne6  14.Nc4  Nd5  The position is approximately equal, but White plays somewhat inaccurately with:  15.Qc2 ?!  after which  Nxc3  16.Qxc3  e4  17.d4  Ng5  led to a very pleasant position for Black. His attacking perspectives on the kingside are obvious, and the game continued  18.Ne5  Bh3  19.f4  exf3  20.Nxf3  Bxg2  21.Kxg2  Qd5  22.Rb2  Ne4  ∓  after which it seems the first player player was saved by his higher rating when he offered his opponent a draw and got it. 1/2-1/2  (22)  Crosa Coll,M  (2449)  -Borges,L  (2303)  Sao Jose do Rio Preto 2006  11...h6  12.Bb2  After   12.e3  Black has a choice between  Bf5  And   12...Be6  13.Ne4  b6 =  leads to easy equality as well.  13.Ne4  b6  14.Qc2  Qd7 =  Black has harmoniously arranged his pieces and can safely look to the future.  15.Nh4  Bh3  There was a good alternative   15...Rad8 !?  with the idea  16.Nxf5  gxf5  17.Nc3  Qxd3  16.Bxh3  Qxh3  17.Nc3  Rad8  18.b5  axb5  19.Nxb5  Rd7  =+  Sulypa, A  (2478)  -Pinski,J  (2362)  Warsaw 2006  12...Be6  13.Ne4  b6  A very solid set up for Black. The vulnerable squares on g5 and c5 are covered. Next he can connect his rooks by finding a good square for the queen.  14.Qc2  Qd7  15.Rfe1  Nd4  Or   15...Rfd8  16.Rbc1  Ra7  Intending a6-a5, followed by Nc6-d4.   16...Rac8  17.Qa4  Ra8  16.Nxd4  exd4  17.Rbc1  Rac8  18.Qb1  Bd5  1/2-1/2  (18)  Perez Aleman,P  (2280)  -Garcia Fernandez,C  (2390)  Mesa 1992 }
10. a3 O-O 11. b4
{ 11.Bg5  instead is sort of pointless after  h6  12.Bd2  Be6  13.b4  axb4  14.axb4  b6   14...Nd4 =  15.Ne1  Rc8  16.b5  Nd4 =  Dumpor,A  (2406)  -Rogic,D  (2523)  Banja Vrucica 2009 }
11... axb4 12. axb4 Nd4
{ Once again a matter of taste. Do we do this immediately, or do we wait for White to attack our knight ?  Either way is fine as practice shows:   12...h6 !?  Check out this model game now !  13.b5  Nd4  14.Nxd4  Or   14.Nd2  Ra7  15.Bb2  b6  16.Ra1  Rxa1  17.Bxa1  Bg4  18.Re1  Bd7   18...Qd7 =  19.Qb1  g5  20.e3  Ndf5  21.Rc1  Nd6 =  Ilic,S  (2250)  -Ristic,N  (2370)  Nisz 1995  14...exd4  15.Ne4  Nd5  16.Bb2  b6  Always a great idea. Black is silently surrounding the centralized knight by taking away the c5-square.  Developing with   16...Be6  is fine too as Black does not need to fear  17.Nc5  Qe7  18.Nxe6   18.Nxb7 ?  Ra7  traps the knight.  18...Qxe6 =  17.Qc2   17.e3  was a must to create counterplay.  17...Ra5 !  =+  This is one of the reasons why, as Black, I like to see the pawn on b5. It might easily become a target for Black's pieces  18.Bc1  Makes things easier for Black.  f5  19.Bd2   19.Nd2  Nc3 !  19...Ra7  And the knight got trapped in the middle of the board ! A thing to remember for the future. White resigned a few moves later:  20.Qc4  Be6  21.Qc6  Bf7  22.Rfd1  Qe8  23.Ra1  Qxc6  24.bxc6  Rfa8  25.Rxa7  Rxa7  26.Rc1  fxe4  27.dxe4  Nc3  28.Bf3  b5  0-1  (28)  Novakovic,D  (2303)  -Rogic,D  (2555)  Babina Greda 2014 }
13. Nd2
{ 13.Bg5  doesn't yield White anything after  f6  14.Be3  f5  The patient   14...Be6  15.Ne4  b6 =  was more to the point.  15.Qd2   15.Bg5 !?  Be6  16.Nxd4  exd4  17.Bxb7  Rb8  18.Nd5  Rxb7  19.Nxe7+  Kf7  15...Kh8  16.Bg5  Qd6  17.Nxd4  exd4  18.Bxe7  Here:   18.Nb5 !  Qd7  19.Qf4  would have been awkward for Black.  18...Qxe7 =  Petran,P  (2332)  -Kanovsky,D  (2338)  Cartak 2005 }
13... c6 14. e3 Ne6 { The position is approximately equal. } 15. Qc2
{ Or   15.Nc4  Nd5  16.Bd2  Nec7  17.Nxd5  cxd5  18.Nb6  Ra2  19.Nxc8  Qxc8 =  Miciano,J  (2381)  -Van Foreest,J  (2636)  Vlissingen 2018 }
15... Nd5
{ There are other interesting moves.  Like   15...f5 !?  16.b5  Nc5  17.bxc6  bxc6  18.d4  exd4  19.exd4  Ne6 =  Avoiding the possible pin after:   19...Bxd4  20.Nb3  Nxb3  21.Qxb3+  Kh8  22.Rd1  ±  Or   15...b5 !?  16.Nb3  f5  17.Na5  Ra6  18.Rd1  Qd6 =  slowly moving forward. }
16. b5 Nxc3 17. Qxc3 e4
{ The computer claims equality after:   17...cxb5  18.Rxb5  Bd7  19.Rxb7  Rc8  20.Qa3  White is suffering from the pin in case of:   20.Nc4  e4  21.d4  Bc6  22.Rb4  Bd5  20...Nc5  but this is difficult for the human eyes to find. }
18. d4 c5 19. Nxe4 cxd4 20. Qb3 { 20.Qb4 !? } 20... Re8
{ Both   20...Qa5 !?  And   20...Qe7 !?  were more accurate. } 21. Ba3 Ng5
{ Another curious, computer-generated line runs:   21...b6  22.Nf6+  Bxf6  23.Bxa8  dxe3  24.fxe3  Nd4  25.exd4  Bxd4+  26.Kg2  Be6  27.Qf3  Qxa8  28.Qxa8  Rxa8 }
22. Nxg5 Qxg5 23. exd4 Bxd4 24. Qb4
