1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. e3
{ White intends to play the Reversed Taimanov/ Scheveningen. This is quite a flexible set up and the Taimanov can easily transpose into the Scheveningen. The major difference in comparison to the Reversed Dragon is that White's light squared bishop is not as actively posted on the long diagonal. White slowly deploys his forces, looking for a good moment to strike in the centre with either d4 followed by e4, or the other way around. Playing on the queenside remains a good idea for White too. However, as Uncle Yermo  (Alex Yermolinsky)  often says "What works for Black does not necessarily work for White !" We shall see in the following lines that all these plans are not dangerous if we play correctly. }
3... Nc6
{ I suggest this move order, mainly to be prepared to deal with the immediate central push 4. d2-d4 !? The centre is of special value for the chess game, especially in the opening, it always makes sense to keep a close eye on it. }
4. a3
{ Definitely not the main move, but one of the many that might lead to the same. There are the following options:   4.d3  g6  would most likely transpose to the text and does not have independent meaning. }
4... g6 5. d3
{ Also possible was going for quick queenside development, typical for many Sicilians with   5.b4  Bg7  6.Bb2  O-O  the dangers behind this move order was demonstrated in the model game Van Wely,L  (2655)  -Kasparov,G  (2820)  Tilburg 1997 CBM 061 }
5... Bg7 6. Nf3 O-O 7. Be2 d5 8. cxd5 Nxd5
{ So here we are, in another Fianchetto line, this time against the Scheveningen. It may arise after this move order 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. g3 e6 7. Bg2 Be7 8. O-O Nc6 as was played in the game Karpov,Anatoly  (2679)  - Fragkiadakis,Manolis, Rethymno sim Rethymno, 2001.  1  Luckily for White he is to move, otherwise Black could have played like Karpov 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. e5 Nd5 11. exd6 Qxd6 12. Ne4 claiming a slight, but long-term advantage thanks to the better queenside pawn structure. }
9. Bd2 { Defending against this threat of Nxc3. } 9... a5
{ Discouraging White's idea of advancing his queenside pawns. However, this is not the only plan that leads to equality ! In fact, we have many. }
10. O-O { 10.Nxd5  Qxd5  11.Bc3  Rd8  only centralizes Black's pieces } 10...
Be6
{ Besides this obvious developing move it is once again Black who has huge choice of decent continuations. }
11. Na4
{ Heading for c5.  There is also   11.Rb1  Nb6  12.Ne4  Qe7  13.b4  axb4  14.axb4  When the most energetic way was:  f5  Instead of the immediate   14...Ba2  15.Rb2  Nd8  16.b5  Re8  17.Qc1  h6  18.Nc5  e4  19.Nxe4  Bxb2  20.Qxb2  =∞  with complications Epishin,V  (2578)  - Ivanov,J  (2370)  Erandio 2007  15.Nc5  Ba2  16.Rc1  The rook cannot step onto the a-file because of   16.Ra1  e4  16...e4  17.Ne1  Nd5  and Black will have the initiative  But perhaps Moro should have done this via the centre:   11.Ne4  b6  12.Qc2  Nde7 = }
11... b6 { Now the knight on a4 looks a bit sad. } 12. Qc2 { 12.Rc1  Nde7 = }
12... Nce7 13. b4 axb4 14. axb4 Qd7
{ White's queenside play is over, Karjakin can concentrate on playing on the opposite flank now. }
15. Rfb1 { 15.Ng5  is not impressive after  Bg4  16.f3  Bh6 ! } 15... h6 16. g3
Bg4 17. e4 { Weakens d4 which Karjakin skillfully exploits. } 17... Bxf3 18.
Bxf3 Nc6 19. exd5 Nd4 20. Qd1 Nxf3+ 21. Qxf3 Rxa4
{ Yep, finally this guy suffered. } 22. Rxa4 Qxa4 23. Rc1 Qd7 24. Rc6 b5
{ fixes White's b-pawn on the color of its own bishop, limiting its mobility. }
25. d6 cxd6 26. Qd5 Ra8 { 26...Rd8 !?  27.Qxb5  d5 } 27. Kg2
{ Too sophisticated.   27.Rxd6  should have been played. } 27... Bf8 28. Rb6
Ra3 29. Rxb5 Qf5 30. Rb8
{ 30.Be3  Rxd3  31.Qa8  was the right way, with a probable draw. } 30... Kg7
{ Black's king is surprisingly viable after   30...Rxd3  31.Qa8  Rxd2  32.Rxf8+  Kg7  33.Rg8+  Kf6  34.Qd8+  Ke6  35.Re8+  Kd5 ! }
31. Bxh6+ Kxh6 32. Rxf8 Kg7 33. Rd8 { 33.b5 !? } 33... Rxd3 34. Qa8 e4 35. Rg8+
Kf6 36. Qd8+ Ke5 37. Qe7+
{ 37.Re8+ !  Kd5  38.Qa5+  Kc4  39.Qxf5  gxf5  40.h4  was the way. } 37... Kd5
38. Qb7+ Kc4 39. Qc8+
{ Now the trade is bad as White does not have a passer on the kingside. } 39...
Qxc8 40. Rxc8+ Kxb4 41. Rf8 Rf3 42. h4 d5 43. g4 d4 44. h5 gxh5 45. gxh5 Rf6
46. Re8 Rh6 47. Rxe4 Kc3 48. Rh4
{ The final blunder.   48.Rf4  would have likely held. } 48... d3 49. Rf4 d2 *

