1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e5 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. d3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4
{ The only major move that has independent flavour. White is heading for the Classical Sicilian Reversed.   6.e3  would most likely transpose to the game Morozevich-Karjakin  (Reversed Scheveningen)  after  g6  An independent try is:  7.d4  But it does not promise White anything after:  exd4  8.Nxd4  Bg7  9.Nxc6   9.Bb5  is an empty threat after  O-O !  Then  10.Nxc6   10.Bxc6 ?!  Nxc3  11.bxc3  bxc6  ∓  10...Nxc3  11.Qxd8  Rxd8  12.Nxd8  Nxb5  Leaves White's knight in serious trouble. Luckily for White he can save it with a counter-sacrifice:  13.O-O  Nd6  14.Rd1  Bf5  15.Rxd6  cxd6  16.Nxb7  but then White needs to work hard for the equality, say:  a5 !  17.a4  Ra6  18.Bd2  Bxb2  19.Re1  d5  20.Nxa5  Bc2  ∓  9...bxc6  10.Nxd5  Qxd5  11.Qxd5  cxd5  the strong bishop on the long diagonal secures Black a tiny edge, Savon,V  (2465)  -Yakovich, Y  (2530)  Belgorod 1991  Whereas   6.g3  g6  7.Bg2  Nde7  would transpose to the reversed Dragon  (see chapter 2) }
6... Nf6
{ You already know my logic about the positional systems against the reversed Sicilians and I hope you are not surprised by this choice. I believe that the knight is more useful here than on b6. It leaves the b6- square available for his own dark squared bishop once that's been developed to c5 from where it can play an active role on the a7-g1 diagonal. Also, the knight on f6 is much more centralized and can sometimes jump into g4. Our play is easy and straightforward. The plan is to control, and eventually occupy, the d4-square and put pressure on the backwards d3-pawn. And, maybe even put one of our pieces on the d4-square. We're aiming for a position where we have the strategical advantage of having either a good knight on d4 versus a poor bishop on e2, or get an opposite-colored bishops endgame where ours is posted on d4 !  NOTE: Alas, we cannot easily get into our beloved fianchettoe with   6...Nde7  as this is one of those cases where the extra tempo really matters:  7.Be3  g6  8.d4 !  is awkward for Black.  Of course   6...Nb6  has gotten Black satisfactory results as well. }
7. Be2
{ White can also start with:   7.h3  which avoids allowing Black to trade off his light squared bishop by way of 7... Bg4, 8... Bxf3 which would lessen White's control over the d4-square. Since this is not what we intend to play we are not impressed and can continue with our move  Bc5  which also fights for the d4-square but keeps both of Black's bishops on the board.  8.Be2  h6  Or simpler   8...O-O  which was the actual course of the game Krysa,L  (2423)  -Rodriguez Vila,A  (2532)  Moroni 2012, see below.  9.O-O  O-O  10.Be3  Bb6  11.b4  Re8 =  led to a similar situation to the one in our featured game in Andreasson,I  (2363)  - Rydstrom,T  (2307)  Sweden 2017   7.Be3  allows  Ng4  where we see the utility of the knight. }
7... Bc5 { Aiming at the vital d4-square. } 8. O-O O-O 9. h3
{ 9.a3  does not even create a threat and we can go  Bg4  10.Be3  Bb6 =   10...Qe7 = }
9... Re8 { Protects e5 and prepares Black's next knight move. } 10. Be3 Nd4 11.
Rc1 c6
{ IMPORTANT: An instructive moment. I already mentioned a method that White often applies in order to cover the weakness on d4 in the game Caruana-Karjakin. This method consists of a timely trade on d4 that forces Black to capture with the pawn. By doing so White achieves three things: 1  Plugs the hole on d4 so that Black's pieces can no longer use it. 2  Blocks the half-open d-file which secures his backward d3 pawn. 3  Creates a kingside pawn majority so that White can start attacking there. This is the reason why Tomashevsky moves the pawn from c7, so that his queen no longer needs to protect it.  Strictly speaking there is nothing wrong with other careful moves like:   11...b6  12.Bxd4  exd4  and this position is also playable as we have the two bishops. Especially if White plays passively like in the following game:  The situation that I described above arises after   12...Bxd4  13.Nxd4  exd4  14.Nb5  c5  15.f4  a6  16.Na3  Bb7  17.Bf3  when White's kingside prospects are better.  13.Nb1  However   13.Nb5 !?  is an improvement with the idea:  a6   13...a5 =  14.Nxc7 !  Qxc7  15.b4  +=  13...Nh5  14.Nbd2  Nf4  =+  with an obvious edge for Black, Krysa,L  (2423)  -Rodriguez Vila,A  (2532)  Moroni 2012 }
12. Na4
{ Here   12.Bxd4  can be answered  Bxd4  13.Nxd4  Qxd4  =+  and the c7 pawn is no longer hanging. }
12... Nxf3+ 13. Bxf3 Bd4 14. Qd2 Qd6 { Black has no problems whatsoever. } 15.
b4 h6 16. Bxd4 Qxd4 17. Nc5 Re7 18. Qc3 Qxc3 19. Rxc3 b6 20. Nb3 Ba6 21. Rd1
{ Correctly avoiding:   21.Rxc6  Bxd3  22.Re1  Bb5  =+ } 21... Bb5 22. d4 Rae8
23. dxe5 { Not   23.d5  cxd5  24.exd5  Rd7  =+ } 23... Rxe5 24. Nd4 Ba4 25.
Rdc1
{ Perhaps White should have settled for a draw with something like:   25.Nxc6  Nxe4  26.Nxe5  Nxc3  27.Rd3  Nxa2  28.Ra3  Rxe5  29.Rxa4  Nc1  30.Rxa7  Nd3  31.Rb7  Nxb4  32.Rxb6 = }
25... c5 26. bxc5 Nxe4 27. Bxe4 Rxe4 28. Nb3 Kf8
{ Now Black avoids the draw after:   28...Bxb3  29.axb3  bxc5  30.Rxc5  Re1+  31.Rxe1  Rxe1+  32.Kh2  Rb1 = }
29. Rc4 { 29.c6 !  was a must. } 29... Bd7 30. f3 Rxc4 31. Rxc4 Rc8 32. Rd4 Ke7
33. cxb6 axb6
{ Black is better thanks to his superior minor piece, although White should have been able to defend this. }
34. Rb4 b5 35. Re4+ Kd8 36. Kf2 Ra8 37. Re2 Kc7 38. Kg3 Be6 39. Nd4 Bc4 40.
Nxb5+ { Presumably missing Black's next in the time trouble. } 40... Kb6
{ White was hoping for   40...Bxb5  41.Re7+  Kd6  42.Rxf7  Rg8  43.Ra7  with good chances for a draw. }
41. Nc3 Bxe2 42. Nxe2 Rxa2 { Now Black wins. } 43. Nf4 Kc5 44. h4 Kd4 45. Nh3
Ke3 46. Nf4 Ra5 47. Nh3 Ke2 48. Kh2 Kf1 49. Nf4 Ra4 50. Kg3 Rxf4 *

