[Black "Huston, Scott vs. Shirov, Alexei"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this game we shall see some less explored but perfectly playable continuations that we could face. }
1. c4
{ The early a2-a3 is possible even on move one-   1.a3  Although, the normal move order will be 1. c4 e5 2. a3  e5  2.c4  Nf6  3.Nc3  then I suggest that we fianchetto at once  g6  waiting for a good moment to play d5. This can easily transpose to either the Reversed Accelerated Dragon or to the game Rechlis-Gelfand. Some independent tries are  4.Nf3  Nc6  5.g3  Bg7  6.Bg2  O-O  7.O-O  d5  8.cxd5  Nxd5  9.Nxe5  finally transposes into Rechlis-Gelfand.  Or into the main lines with   9.d3 }
1... e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 d5 { Finally, one more rare move is: } 4. Nc3
{ But this move simply allows Black a chance to grab more space in the centre and is just good for Black after the obvious   4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.Nc3  Ne7  would transpose to chapter two. }
4... d4 5. Ne4
{ There is no better spot for the knight.   5.Nb1 ?!  is just loss of two tempi and Black quickly got the upper hand after  c5  6.d3  Nc6  7.Nf3  Bd6  8.Na3  O-O  9.O-O  h6  10.Nc2  Re8  11.a3  a5  =+  Jurman,R  (2103)  -Zufic, M  (2457)  Pula 2015  On the other hand   5.Na4 ?!  is even worse  d3  was OK for Black after  However   5...c6 !  N  underlines the delicate situation of the knight and confirms Black's advantage. Say:  6.d3  Be6  7.Nf3  Nbd7  8.Ng5  b5  ∓  trapping the knight.  6.exd3  Be7  7.Nf3  Nc6  8.O-O  Qxd3 =  Cernik,L  (2202)  -Kulhanek, T  (2375)  Nachod 2011 }
5... Nxe4 6. Bxe4 Nd7 7. d3 Be7 8. e3 Nc5 9. exd4 Nxe4 10. dxe4 exd4
{ The endgame might be even better-   10...Qxd4  11.Qxd4  exd4  12.Ne2  c5  =+ }
11. Ne2 c5 12. Nf4 O-O 13. O-O Bd6
{ With simple play Black got the bishop pair and a strong defended central passed pawn. Shirov went on to win comfortably. }
14. Nd5 f5 15. exf5 Bxf5 16. Bf4 Be6 17. Bxd6 Qxd6 18. Rc1 Bxd5 19. cxd5 Qxd5
20. b3 d3 21. Rc3 Rad8 22. Qd2 Rf3 23. Rfc1 b6 24. Re1 Rdf8 25. Rf1 h5 26. h4
b5 27. a3 c4 28. bxc4 bxc4 29. Qa2 Rxg3+ 30. fxg3 Rxf1+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Dubov, Daniil vs. Karjakin, Sergey"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e5 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 Bc5
{ "A very popular line of late"  (Dubov) } 7. O-O O-O 8. d3
{ Aronian's treatment of the line was cruel:   8.Nxd5  Qxd5  9.Ng5  Qd8  10.Nxh7  Re8  11.Ng5  Qxg5  12.Bxc6  bxc6  13.d4  Aronian,L  (2799)  -Caruana,F  (2807)  Saint Louis 2017 }
8... Bb6
{ In order to avoid the following forcing lines and to overprotect the e5 pawn. This is why we have it as our main move in this repertoire. Still, it is useful to check the other main line.   8...Re8 }
9. Nxd5 Qxd5 10. b4 e4 11. Ng5 Qd4
{ Obviously this whole sequence of moves was no revelation for either of the players. Now comes the novelty. }
12. Ba3
{ "I do not think that this novelty leads to an advantage if he plays correctly, but at least Black needs to remember a lot of stuff."  (Dubov)  Remarkably, the two previous games in this line were played by Karjakin. Both against Nakamura, only a month before   12.Be3  Qxb4  13.Nxe4  Bxe3  Black also tried:   13...Bg4  although this seems less convincing-  14.h3  Bh5  15.Rb1  Qe7  16.Qd2  Rad8  17.Nc3  Nakamura,H  (2792)  -Karjakin,S  (2773)  Saint Louis 2017  14.fxe3  Qe7  15.Qd2  Ne5  16.Rac1  c6  with approximate equality, Nakamura,H  (2792)  -Karjakin,S  (2773)  Saint Louis }
12... e3
{ Correct.  Whereas   12...exd3  13.b5  Nb4  14.e3  Qc3  15.Bxb4  Qxb4  16.Qxd3  favours White. }
13. b5 exf2+ 14. Kh1 Ne5
{ Correct again.   14...Nb4 ?  puts the knight in a precarious situation. White can capitalize on that with:  15.Qb3  Bc5  16.Nf3  Qd6  17.d4 }
15. Bxf8 Kxf8 16. a4 a5
{ It is essential to keep the dark-squared bishop alive. It should be added that both players played quite comfortably until this moment, practically blitzing out their moves.  If   16...h6  17.a5  hxg5  18.Ra4  Qd6  19.axb6  Qxb6  20.Qc1  White is clearly better. }
17. bxa6 Rxa6 18. a5 Ba7
{ The first long think for Karjakin  (25 minutes.)  And a mistake according to Dubov.   18...Rxa5 !  was the right way to play it is what Dubov revealed in the short post-game interview.   18...Bxa5  is not as convincing instead and White is doing great after  19.Ra4  Qe3  20.Nxh7+  Kg8  21.Re4  Qd2  22.Qxd2  Bxd2  23.Rxe5 }
19. Qc1
{ "I thought this was clever. I only rememebered that the computer evaluation was better for me. From now on we played on our own".  Dubov  The queen becomes active with an attack on the c7-pawn, gaining a tempo.   19.Qb3  also looks interesting. }
19... Qd8
{ 19...h6  20.Qxc7  loses instantly.   19...Qd6  only helps White after  20.Ne4   19...c6 !?  was the only other option, although White seems better after both:  20.Nxh7+  Or   20.Ne4  Ng4  21.Bh3  But not   21.h3  Ne3  22.Rxf2  Nxg2  23.Kxg2  Qd7 !  with counterplay for Black.  21...Qe5  22.Qa3+  c5   22...Kg8  23.Qd6  23.Bxg4  Bxg4  24.Rxf2  20...Kg8  21.Ng5  The pawn on f2 is unpleasant, but if White manages to consolidate and surrounded it he will be winning. }
20. Qf4 { The queen is perfectly placed here. } 20... h6 21. Ne4 Qe7
{ Worse is   21...Bd4  22.Rac1  Rxa5  23.Nxf2  without that pawn Black does not have any play. }
22. Nc3
{ 22.Nxf2 ?  is bad due to  Rf6 !  However   22.Rac1 !?  deserves attention with the idea of  Rxa5  23.Nxf2 }
22... g5
{ Apparently Karjakin disliked the endgame after   22...c6  23.Ne4  Or   23.Nd1  Ng4  24.d4  g5  25.Qd2  Qd6  which is also not so clear.  23...Ng4  24.Bh3  g5  25.Qd6  h5  but in the game he would get a much worse version of it ! }
23. Qc1 { With the strong threat Nc3-d5 ! } 23... Ng4
{ Even after   23...c6  there is  24.Nd5 !   24.Ne4  is not as convincing after  Ng4  25.h3  Ne3  24...Qd6  25.Nb6 !  As mentioned earlier, this is Black's key piece and once that it disappears from the board all Black's counterplay dries up. For example:  Bxb6  26.axb6  Rxa1  27.Qxa1  Ng4  28.Qh8+  Ke7  29.Qxc8  and White wins. }
24. Nd5 Qxe2 25. Qxc7 Rc6
{ Dubov was more worried about moves that kept the queens on the board as time-trouble was approaching.  Still, the engine reveals wins for White in both cases. After:   25...Be6  26.Qxb7  Nxh2  Or   26...Bxd5  27.Bxd5  Rf6  28.Qxa7  27.Qe7+  Kg7  28.Qf6+  It is White who mates first:  Kg8   28...Kf8  29.Qh8#   28...Kh7  29.Be4+  29.Ne7+  Kf8  30.Ng6+  Ke8  31.Qe7#  And:   25...Bf5  26.Qxb7  Nxh2  27.Qxa6  Nxf1  28.Qxh6+  allows White a chance to defend against the checkmate just in time. }
26. Qd8+ Qe8
{ The endgame is lost according to both players.  However there was no alternative-   26...Kg7  27.Ne7  Rc2  28.Qg8+  Kf6  29.Nxc8  leaves Black no pieces. }
27. Qxe8+ Kxe8 28. d4 { "The most convincing win"  (Dubov) } 28... Kd8
{ Or the familiar bishop blockade theme after   28...Bxd4  29.Ra4  Ba7  30.Nb6 }
29. h3 Nf6 30. Nb6 Rc2 31. Nxc8
{ 31.Nxc8  Kxc8   31...Rxc8  32.Rxf2  32.Rac1  Rxc1  33.Rxc1+  Kb8  34.Rb1 } *

