[Black "Kramnik, Vladimir vs. Karjakin, Sergey"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e5
{ Remember what I wrote previously, that the English is a popular opening choice in rapid and the blitz events ? }
3. Nf3 Nc6 4. d3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e3
{ Instead of fianchettoeing his bishop Kramnik chooses a solid Classical/ Scheveningen set up. In his youth he was one of the greatest Classical Sicilian specialists in the world. }
6... Be7 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O Be6 9. a3 a5 10. Bd2
{ 10.Qc2  had also been seen. One recent example ran:  Qd7  11.Bd2  Rfd8  12.Na4  f6  13.Rfc1  Kh8  14.Nc5  Bxc5  15.Qxc5  a4  16.Be1  Nde7  17.Nd2  b6  18.Qc2  Bg4  19.Bf1  Be6  20.Be2  Bg4  21.Bf1  Be6  22.Be2  1/2-1/2  (22)  Zhou,J  (2612)  -Zhao,J  (2634)  China 2016 }
10... Kh8
{ Quite a useful prophylactical move.   10...f5  can be met with  11.e4 } 11.
Rc1
{ This logical move is a novelty. White intends Nc3-e4   a4  -c5.  The only predecessor saw a quick draw after:   11.Nxd5  Qxd5  12.Bc3  f6  13.Qc2  a4  14.d4  exd4  15.Nxd4  Nxd4  16.Bxd4  c5  17.Bc3  Bf5  1/2-1/2  (17)  Visser,D  (2126)  -Seidel,J  (2010)  Niederrhein 2003 }
11... Nxc3 12. Rxc3
{ Somewhat artificial. Kramnik intends to sacrifice the exchange on c6, but no one is going to allow this.   12.Bxc3  is more sound, with approximate equality after  f6  Black is not afraid of the central strike  13.d4  as he can block the centre after  e4  14.Nd2  f5 }
12... f6 13. Qa4
{ The idea idea behind the capture of the rook. White now intends Rf1-c1. But it has a cute refutation. }
13... Nb4
{ Not only prevents the doubling of the rooks, but it also prepares the advance of the c7-pawn to c5. The Maroczy bind position that arises after that is favorable for Black. }
14. e4
{ Surely   14.axb4 ?  axb4  is no good for White.  Neither is   14.Rfc1 ?  Na2  But perhaps Kramnik should have admitted that this plan is not great and had returned back home with the queen   14.Qd1  Black would be great in that case too  Nd5  15.Rc1  c5 }
14... c5 15. Be3 b6 16. Nd2 Bd7
{ Karjakin secures the road to d4 for his knight and is already slightly better. }
17. Qd1 Nc6 18. a4 Be6 19. Bg4 Bg8
{ Avoiding the swap of light squared bishops and keeping his "good" bishop alive. }
20. Nc4 Bd6
{ Another nice maneuver, the bishop is heading to the b8-h2 diagonal, in anticipation of the f2-f4 advance. The bishop can also relieve Black's queen from the defense of the b6 pawn. }
21. g3 Bc7 22. Na3
{ White continues to maneuver on the queenside.  As   22.f4  would be answered with  exf4 !  23.gxf4  Qe7  followed by Ra8-d8 and pressure against the d3 pawn. }
22... Qe7 23. Nb5 Rad8 24. h4
{ If   24.Nxc7  Qxc7  with clear play against the backward d3 pawn. } 24... Bb8
25. h5
{ Kramnik did everything right and patienlty improved what could have been improved. }
25... Qe8
{ Karjakin also continues maneuvering.  Two other options deserved attention too. One was to sacrifice a pawn with   25...Nd4  26.Bxd4  exd4  27.Rc1  c4  28.dxc4  d3  The other was to try and pressurize on d3   25...Nb4  although it is not as easy as it seems after  26.Qe2 }
26. Kg2 Ne7 { The point behind the previous move. The idea is f6-f5. } 27. Qe2
{ And this only makes things easier for Black. Although it is difficult to suggest anything creative for him.   27.Rh1  f5 ! }
27... f5 28. exf5 Nxf5
{ Without the e4-pawn White has huge difficulties defending his kingside. } 29.
Bg5 Nd4 { And this move is more effective. } 30. Qd1
{ Making it even more difficult for him.  However Black is clearly better after   30.Nxd4  exd4  31.Qxe8  Rdxe8  32.Rcc1  h6 !  as well. For example:  33.Bh4  Or   33.Bd2  Bh7 !  33...Bd6 }
30... Nxb5 31. axb5 Rd4 { One more excellent move. } 32. Be3
{ If   32.Bf3  Rxf3 !  wins on the spot  33.Kxf3   33.Qxf3  Bd5  33...Qxh5+ }
32... Bd5+ 33. Kg1 { 33.f3 ?  Rxg4 } 33... Rb4
{ Black is winning a pawn and keeps all the advantages of his position. The game is essentially over. }
34. h6
{ Kramnik's last resort is tactics but Karjakin has those available as well ! }
34... gxh6 35. Bxh6 Qg6 { Powerful and strong. } 36. Bxf8 Rxg4
{ Threatening mate. } 37. Qe1 Rh4
{ Forces a decisive weakening of White's position. } 38. f3 Rh3
{ The rest is easy for Karjakin. } 39. Kg2 Qh5 40. Qe3 Rh2+ 41. Kg1 Qh3 42.
Bg7+ Kg8 { Avoiding the unnecessary checks after   42...Kxg7  43.Qg5+  Kf7 } *

