1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Bg2 Ne7 6. Nf3
{ For   6.h4  please check the next file. } 6... Nbc6 7. h4
{ White shows his cards too early. There is nothing to attack yet on the kingside. Moreover, the move itself could be a weakening in the future. }
7... Nf5
{ We can proceed with the development and show flexibility, completely giving up the fianchettoe.  There was also a game after:   7...h6  8.h5  Be6  9.Qa4  Qd7  10.b4  Nd4  11.b5  Nxf3+  12.Bxf3  Nd5  where Black did well in the opening and in fact won quickly, Buenafe Moya,J  (2303)  -Garcia Fernandez,C  (2370)  Manises 2004  Now the most obvious move is: }
8. O-O
{ Also logical is:   8.b4  To which we can try either:  a6  Or the more risky  (and rewarding !)   8...Bxb4  9.Nxe5  Nxe5  10.Qa4+  Nc6  11.Bxc6+  bxc6  12.Qxb4  Nd4  Our pawn structure is a mess, but the black king is safer and we can mount pressure on the light squares. For example:  13.Qa4   13.Kd1  loses the right to castle.  13...O-O  14.O-O  Re8  15.e3  Nf3+  16.Kg2  Qd3 !  ∓  With the threat of Bc8-h3+ !  9.Bb2  Be7  10.Ne4  White should be aware that his b4 pawn might be hanging in some lines:   10.e3 ?  Bxb4  With the idea:  11.Nxe5  Nxe5  12.Qa4+  Bd7  13.Qxb4 ??  Nd3+   10.O-O  O-O  Will be similar to the main line.  10...Nfd4  The standart move in the main line. Black is good after:  11.Nxd4  exd4  12.Qa4  Or   12.Nc5  O-O  13.Qa4  Re8  ⇆  Underlining the fact that White did not castle yet.  12...O-O  You should not fear:  13.b5  Na7  14.bxa6   14.Qxd4  Qxd4  15.Bxd4  axb5  is equal.  14...Nc6  with good play for Black.  But after: }
8... Be7
{ The whole idea behind h2-h4 makes no sense at all. Black will proceed with O-O, Nf5-d4, and kingside attack with f7-f5-   f4  or e5-e4 as in the main lines. The inclusion of the h2-h4 will facilitate his play. }
